uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been used in research studies exploring machine learning approaches for prediction of patient outcomes.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: Yes, data represents people as is collected from people
uses_collected_from_people: Yes, the subjects of the collection process are humans. This is indicated by the mention of unique patients, admissions to the hospital, and admissions to intensive care units in the context.
uses_biases: No. The context does not provide any information about biases issues of the data.
uses_sensitivity: Yes, the context mentions that the data was deidentified in accordance with Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) standards. This means that identifying data elements such as patient name, telephone number, and address were removed. Additionally, dates were shifted into the future and ages were obscured to comply with HIPAA regulations. Therefore, the data is not sensitive and should not be offensive to anyone.
uses_privacy: Yes, the context provides information about privacy issues of the data. The context mentions that researchers are required to complete a recognized course in protecting human research participants that includes Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) requirements. Additionally, researchers must sign a data use agreement that outlines appropriate data usage and security standards and forbids efforts to identify individual patients. The deidentification process is also described, which involves removing identifying data elements and using a deidentification system to remove protected health information from free text fields.
uses_data: The collected data in the MIMIC-III database consists of 26 tables, which are linked by identifiers such as SUBJECT_ID, HADM_ID, and ICUSTAY_ID. These identifiers represent unique patients, admissions to the hospital, and admissions to intensive care units, respectively. The database includes various types of data, ranging from time-stamped physiological measurements to free-text interpretations of imaging studies. The data is stored in tables such as ADMISSIONS, PATIENTS, ICUSTAYS, SERVICES, TRANSFERS, D_CPT, D_ICD_DIAGNOSES, D_ICD_PROCEDURES, D_ITEMS, and D_LABITEMS. These tables define and track patient stays, cross-reference codes against their definitions, and contain data associated with patient care, such as physiological measurements, caregiver observations, and billing information. The data is provided as comma-separated value (CSV) files, along with scripts to import the data into database systems. Access to the data requires researchers to complete a recognized course in protecting human research participants and sign a data use agreement that outlines appropriate data usage and security standards. Once approved, researchers can download the database from PhysioNetWorks.
collection_explanation:
The dataset, MIMIC-III, was collected from the Beth Israel Deaconess Medical Center. The collection process aimed to minimize structural changes to ensure that the dataset closely represents the raw data collected within the medical center. Best practices for scientific computing were followed, including version control and collaborative development of the code used to build the dataset. This approach facilitated sharing of readable code and documentation, as well as feedback from colleagues. Issue tracking was used to document limitations of the data and code, and a system for releasing minor database updates was implemented.

MIMIC-III is a relational database consisting of 26 tables. These tables are linked by identifiers, such as SUBJECT_ID, HADM_ID, and ICUSTAY_ID, which represent unique patients, admissions to the hospital, and admissions to intensive care units, respectively. Charted events, such as notes, laboratory tests, and fluid balance, are stored in a series of 'events' tables. For example, the OUTPUTEVENTS table contains measurements related to output for a given patient, while the LABEVENTS table contains laboratory test results. Tables prefixed with 'D_' are dictionary tables that provide definitions for identifiers. By joining these tables with the corresponding 'events' tables, it is possible to identify the concept represented by a given ITEMID.

To access the data, MIMIC-III is provided as a collection of comma-separated value (CSV) files, along with scripts to help with importing the data into database systems. Researchers are required to formally request access and complete a recognized course in protecting human research participants that includes Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA) requirements. They must also sign a data use agreement that outlines appropriate data usage and security standards, and forbids efforts to identify individual patients. Once approved, researchers can download the database from PhysioNetWorks, a restricted access component of PhysioNet.

The MIMIC data model consists of several tables that define and track patient stays, as well as dictionaries for cross-referencing codes against their definitions. The remaining tables contain data associated with patient care, such as physiological measurements, caregiver observations, and billing information. While it would be possible to merge some tables, the approach taken in the MIMIC data model is to keep them independent for clarity, as the data sources are significantly different. Researchers are encouraged to develop database views and transforms as needed.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.

collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include data tables, structured data cleansing and date shifting techniques, deidentification system based on dictionary look-ups and pattern-matching, comma separated value (CSV) files, database systems such as PostreSQL, MySQL, and MonetDB, and PhysioNetWorks for downloading the database.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves linking tables in the MIMIC-III database using identifiers. These identifiers, such as SUBJECT_ID, HADM_ID, and ICUSTAY_ID, represent unique patients, admissions to the hospital, and admissions to the intensive care unit, respectively. Charted events, such as notes, laboratory tests, and fluid balance, are stored in 'events' tables, such as OUTPUTEVENTS and LABEVENTS. Dictionary tables, prefixed with 'D_', provide definitions for identifiers. For example, by joining CHARTEVENTS and D_ITEMS on ITEMID, the concept represented by a given ITEMID can be identified. The MIMIC data model closely represents the raw hospital data and includes tables for patient stays, dictionaries for cross-referencing codes, and tables for patient care data. The TRANSFERS table tracks patient movement within the hospital. Researchers are encouraged to develop database views and transforms as needed.

uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset include making effective mid-season drought forecasts, analyzing recent shifts in decadal precipitation in data sparse regions, supporting humanitarian relief efforts, guiding climate-smart development, exploring the nexus of climate change, population growth, and vegetation declines, identifying links between drought and low birth weights, forcing hydrologic models and simulating near-real time initial hydrologic conditions, contributing to drought prediction skill, capturing hydrologic information for enhanced drought early warning, and evaluating the drought impacts of temperature.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No, the data of the dataset does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset is specifically designed for monitoring agricultural drought and global environmental change over land. It involves climate models, satellite data, and station data.
uses_data: The collected data is a new dataset specifically designed for monitoring agricultural drought and global environmental change over land. It has spatial and temporal coverage, latency, and resolution that is unprecedented for a global terrestrial product. The dataset has been validated and shows good performance for drought monitoring. It can be used in conjunction with land surface models to make mid-season drought forecasts or to analyze recent shifts in decadal precipitation in data sparse regions that depend on convective rainfall. The dataset is called CHIRPS and it involves three main components: the Climate Hazards group Precipitation climatology (CHPclim), the satellite-only Climate Hazards group Infrared Precipitation (CHIRP), and the station blending procedure that produces the CHIRPS. The CHIRPS dataset has been validated and shows promising results, with correlations with wet season GPCC precipitation greater than 0.75 in many areas of the world. The data is available in various formats and spatial resolutions, with units in mm per time period (e.g., mm per day, mm per pentad, mm per month). Supporting data, such as station density, browse images, and lists of locations, are also provided.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected from 3,380 stations in Colombia, obtained from the Instituto de Hidrología, Meteorología y Estudios Ambientales (IDEAM). These stations were initially withheld and monthly 'final' CHIRPS values were estimated. The monthly CHIRPS, CHIRP, CFS, CPC Unified, ECMWF, and GPCC values at the station locations were extracted. The mean of these locations (for each month) was calculated and then summed across the main rainy season (September-November) for each year. The dataset also leverages historical long-term monthly means from the Agromet Group of the Food and Agriculture Organization of the United Nations (FAO) and version two of the Global Historical Climate Network (GHCN) to create the CHPclim dataset. The CHPclim dataset includes information from monthly long-term mean fields from five satellite products. The CHIRP pentads are available on the second day after the end of the pentad, and a monthly preliminary CHIRPS is created as the sum of the six preliminary pentads. Final pentad and monthly station data files are created and quality controlled. Daily CHIRPS is produced using daily CCD data to identify non-precipitating days, and missing CCD days are assumed to be non-precipitating days if the CFS precipitation is less than 3.5 mm per day.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_speakers_demographics: No. The context does not provide information about the speech situation, such as the genre, the modality, or the topics.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Climate Hazards group Precipitation climatology (CHPclim), the satellite-only Climate Hazards group Infrared Precipitation (CHIRP), the station blending procedure, the GPCC dataset, and independent station datasets.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- Climate Hazards group Precipitation climatology (CHPclim)
- Climate Hazards group Infrared Precipitation (CHIRP)
- Station blending procedure
- Satellite data
- Gauge data
- GHCN and GSOD data
- Daily CCD data
- CFS precipitation data
- Sheffield dataset
- GeoCLIM software
- International Research Institute's Enhancing National Climate Time Series (ENACTS) software
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves validating different precipitation datasets for specific regions. In this case, the validation is done for southwestern North America (SWNA) for October-June precipitation. The 'truth' data used for validation are a dense set of GHCN station data block kriged for the region of interest. The validation results compare different datasets, such as CHIRP, CFS, ECMWF, CPC Unified, GPCC, and CHIRPS, in terms of their correlation with the observed data and their bias issues. The CHIRP dataset underestimates the variance of SWNA precipitation but has a reasonable correlation. The CFS and ECMWF datasets tend to overestimate but have high correlation values. The CPC Unified dataset performs well in SWNA but degrades in Colombia after 2002. The CHIRPS dataset is designed to provide GPCC-like performance with lower latencies and has low bias and high correlations with wet season GPCC precipitation in many areas of the world. Overall, the annotation process evaluates the performance of different datasets in terms of their correlation, bias, and suitability for drought monitoring and environmental change detection.

uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset are to provide insights into potential spatial changes in regional climatic zones under climate change and to remove mean biases from climate model outputs in climate change impact assessments.
uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been tested in a machine learning approach. The classification accuracy of the present-day Köppen-Geiger classification was calculated using station observations as a reference. The accuracy of the new map was compared to previous maps, confirming that the new map is more accurate. Additionally, the usefulness of the confidence map associated with the new present-day classification was tested using station observations.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is based on climate data and is used to classify climate into different categories.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are climatic datasets, not humans.
uses_data:
The collected data for this study includes three climatic datasets for air temperature (WorldClim V1 and V2, and CHELSA V1.2) and four climatic datasets for precipitation (WorldClim V1 and V2, CHELSA V1.2, and CHPclim V1). These datasets have a resolution of 0.0083°, except for CHPclim V1.2 which has a resolution of 0.05°. To ensure consistency, CHPclim V1.2 was downscaled to 0.0083° using bilinear interpolation. 

For the future scenario, monthly historical and future air temperature and precipitation data from the CMIP5 archive were used. The future scenario used was Representative Concentration Pathway 8.5 (RCP8.5). All climate models with data during the periods 1980-2016 and 2071-2100 were used. The data for the 1980-2016 period was derived by concatenating historical runs and future runs. Only a single initialization ensemble was considered for each model. In total, 32 models had sufficient data and were used for deriving the future map.

The present-day Köppen-Geiger map was derived from an ensemble of high-resolution climatic datasets using specific criteria. The climatic datasets were adjusted to reflect the period 1980-2016 by calculating monthly climatologies for temperature and precipitation. Climate change offsets or factors were calculated for each month and resampled to a resolution of 0.0083° using bilinear interpolation. The adjusted climatic maps were then used to derive a Köppen-Geiger map at 0.0083° resolution. From this ensemble of maps, a final map was derived by selecting the most common class for each grid-cell. A confidence map was also derived by dividing the frequency of occurrence of the most common class by the ensemble size and converting these fractions to percentages. 

The new high-resolution present-day Köppen-Geiger classification map was validated by calculating the classification accuracy using station observations as a reference. A database was compiled from the Global Historical Climatology Network-Daily (GHCN-D) database and the Global Summary Of the Day (GSOD) database. Monthly mean temperature and precipitation time series were calculated for each station, and monthly climatologies were derived by averaging the monthly means. Stations with gaps in the climatologies or missing data for one of the four maps were discarded. The final dataset comprised 22,078 stations used to calculate the classification accuracy of each map. The newly derived high-resolution present-day Köppen-Geiger classification exhibited a classification accuracy of 80.0%, while the maps from previous studies exhibited lower classification accuracies. 

The usefulness of the confidence map associated with the new present-day classification was also tested using station observations. The mean confidence level was higher for correctly classified stations compared to misclassified stations, indicating that the confidence map provides a useful indication of the classification accuracy. The new present-day map exhibited enhanced detail and better agreement with other high-resolution maps and forest cover maps compared to previous maps.
collection_explanation:
The dataset used in this study was collected through a combination of climatic datasets and station observations. 

For the present Köppen-Geiger classification map, three climatic datasets for air temperature (WorldClim V1 and V2, and CHELSA V1.2) and four climatic datasets for precipitation (WorldClim V1 and V2, CHELSA V1.2, and CHPclim V1) were used. These datasets have a resolution of 0.0083°, except for CHPclim V1.2 which has a resolution of 0.05°. To ensure consistency, CHPclim V1.2 was downscaled to 0.0083° using bilinear interpolation.

For the future Köppen-Geiger classification, monthly historical and future air temperature and precipitation data from the CMIP5 archive were used. The future scenario chosen was Representative Concentration Pathway 8.5 (RCP8.5). All climate models with data during the 1980-2016 and 2071-2100 periods were included in the analysis. The data for the 1980-2016 period was derived by concatenating historical runs and future runs, while considering only a single initialization ensemble for each model. In total, 32 models had sufficient data and were used to derive the future map.

To validate the accuracy of the new high-resolution present-day Köppen-Geiger classification map, station observations were used as a reference. A database was compiled from the Global Historical Climatology Network-Daily (GHCN-D) database and the Global Summary Of the Day (GSOD) database. Monthly mean temperature and precipitation time series were calculated for each station, and monthly climatologies were derived by averaging the monthly means. Stations with gaps in the climatologies or missing data for one of the four maps were discarded. This resulted in a final dataset comprising 22,078 stations, which were used to calculate the classification accuracy of each map.

The newly derived high-resolution present-day Köppen-Geiger classification map exhibited a classification accuracy of 80.0%, while the maps from previous studies had classification accuracies of 66.1%, 70.9%, and 73.4%. The higher accuracy of the new map is attributed to its high resolution and the use of an ensemble of topographically-corrected climatic datasets.

In addition to classification accuracy, the usefulness of the confidence map associated with the new present-day classification was also tested using station observations. The mean confidence level for correctly classified stations was 92.6%, while for misclassified stations it was 77.4%. This confirms that the confidence map provides a useful indication of the classification accuracy.

Overall, the collection process of the dataset involved combining climatic datasets with station observations and validating the accuracy of the classification maps using station observations as a reference.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Validation of temperature using independent meteorological stations.
2. Validation of the dataset's accuracy on a global scale and on a small target scale.
3. Comparison with other reanalysis products.
4. Validation of the dataset's climatological performance.
5. Performance evaluation for species distribution modeling.
uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been tested in a machine learning approach. The performance of the dataset was compared using a species distribution modeling (SDM) approach, where a generalized linear model with mean annual precipitation and mean annual temperature as predictors was used. The models were evaluated using various test measures such as area under the receiver operating characteristic curve (AUC), Kappa statistics, and adjusted D2 value. The performance of the dataset was compared to another climate dataset (WorldClim) and the results showed an improvement when using the CHELSA data.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected includes temperature and precipitation values, which are environmental variables.
uses_data: The collected data includes monthly mean temperature in °C and precipitation values in mm/month, as well as derived bioclimatic variables for the reference period 1979-2013. The data is available in the form of GeoTIFF files and can be freely downloaded from the website www.chelsa-climate.org or from Dryad. The data has been validated using several independent datasets, including FAO-data (400 stations), Mexico-data (2,915 stations), GHCN-data (6,093 stations), and Scandinavia-Nordklim data (32 stations). The validation results show that the downscaled CHELSA data tracks the temperature data well in the GHCN and FAO datasets, but shows larger deviations in the Mexico and Nordklim datasets. The RMSE and MAE values of the Nordklim dataset are comparable to those of the GHCN and FAO datasets, while the comparison with the Mexico dataset shows higher RMSE and MAE values. The climatological performance of the CHELSA data is better than the temporal performance, with lower RMSE and MAE values when compared to all station data. The R2 values are also higher for the climatologies than for the reanalysis values. The validation results for the Mexico dataset show that none of the reanalysis datasets are able to capture the temporal variation in the station dataset well. The average R2 of CHELSA is 0.39, which is slightly better than the performance of CRU and ERA-Interim. The RMSE and MAE values are also lower in their mean and standard deviation. The climatological performance of all models with the Mexico dataset is slightly better than that of the reanalysis dataset. WorldClim shows the highest fit with stations, followed by CHELSA, CHPclim, ERA-Interim, and CRU.
collection_explanation: The dataset used in this study was collected through a validation process using independent precipitation station data. Several independent datasets of various sizes and temporal extents were identified for validation. These datasets were not used in the final bias correction within the algorithm and were screened for duplicates in the GHCN, MeteoSwiss, and DWD datasets. The station data used in the validation process allowed for the validation of the accuracy of the CHELSA algorithm on both the global scale and the target scale of 30 arc°. The validation process was split into two parts: one part examined the temporal performance of the reanalysis dataset, while the other part examined the climatological performance of the dataset. The results of the validation process were compared with other reanalysis products, including the CRU dataset. Additionally, a comparison of the precipitation patterns of the dataset with other products was conducted, using the CRU dataset as a comparison. The large-scale spatial comparison of precipitation patterns served as a guideline for the deviation in the other products but cannot be seen as independent validation.

annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves comparing the CHELSA dataset with other datasets such as FAO, CRU, ERA-Interim, CHPclim, WorldClim, and SAEON. The comparison is done using statistical measures such as R2 (coefficient of determination), root mean square error (RMSE), and mean absolute error. The results of the comparison show that CHELSA has a high correspondence with the FAO dataset, while CRU and ERA-Interim have lower values. The climatological validation shows that CHELSA performs similar to CHPclim and WorldClim, which already include FAO data in some way. CRU and ERA-Interim perform considerably mediocre when compared to FAO data. The validation results indicate that including orographic effects can improve existing climatologies and reanalysis, leading to increasing accuracies in derived analyses such as species distribution models (SDMs). However, CHELSA still exhibits errors, and the improvement varies by region and month. Overall, the validation results suggest that CHELSA is a substantial improvement over existing products for purposes such as SDMs.

authoring_funding: Yes, the CRU TS dataset has been supported by a number of funders, including the UK's Natural Environment Research Council (NERC) and the US Department of Energy.
authoring_funding_grant_id: No, the grant reference numbers are not provided in the given context.
authoring_maintenance_policies: No, there is no mention about maintenance policies of the dataset in the context.
uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset include understanding the level of support behind each grid cell and time step for trend detection or masking of areas, assessing global and regional trend analysis with care taken to avoid trend artifacts, and cross-validation of the interpolated anomalies to assess the skill of the interpolation algorithm and provide a quantitative guide to the expected accuracy of the individual interpolated values.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention of the dataset being tested in any machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: Yes, the context mentions that the user should decide on boundaries to uncertainty for their particular application.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset contains variables related to climate and weather, such as temperature, precipitation, and cloud cover.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of variables related to land surface conditions, such as temperature, precipitation, and cloud cover.
uses_data:
The collected data in the CRU TS v4.03 dataset consists of ten variables of high-resolution global land surface gridded absolute values. These variables include temperature (TMP), diurnal temperature range (DTR), precipitation (PRE), vapor pressure (VAP), wet-day frequency (WET), cloud cover (CLD), minimum temperature (TMN), maximum temperature (TMX), frost day frequency (FRS), and potential evapotranspiration (PET). The data is available in two formats: NetCDF and space-separated ASCII text, to ensure maximum availability for users. The dataset is provided in decadal blocks as well as full-length files. 

The gridded data, except for PET, are accompanied by metadata indicating the level of station support for each datum. The station support varies between 0 (no cover, climatology inserted) and eight (maximum station count for interpolation). The counts produced by interpolation are used for primary (TMP, DTR, PRE) and secondary (VAP, WET, CLD) variables. For derived variables (TMN, TMX, FRS) and PET, the DTR counts are used. PET is calculated using a Penman-Monteith formula and does not have a meaningful station count. The station count metadata is included in the NetCDF files as a second variable and is also published separately as ASCII text files.

An interface is provided in Keyhole Markup Language (KML) format, which allows the dataset to be accessed in Earth browsers such as Google Earth. The Google Earth interface currently supports access to the TMP and PRE data, providing access to individual grid-cell series and station observations in a hierarchical structure.

The dataset includes metadata that enables users to understand the level of support behind each grid cell and time step. This allows for informed detection of trends or masking of areas with limited observation coverage. Temperature data, in particular, has been shown to be resilient to the limitations of sparse data coverage and interpolation.

The dataset is not specifically homogeneous, as some National Meteorological Agencies homogenize their station observations within each country. Additional homogenization on the CRU TS databases is complicated due to synthetic variables and the use of published climatologies. However, comparisons with other datasets indicate that there are no large inhomogeneities present in the CRU TS v4 dataset.

The dataset has been compared with other observation-based datasets at a global scale, demonstrating its robustness. The grids have undergone assessment and validation, which is discussed further in the 'Technical Validation' section of the paper.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through a process of updating meteorological station databases with observations. The process is described in detail in the paper. The databases were updated with observations and used to derive the Diurnal Temperature Range (DTR) database. The observations were collected from various sources, including CLIMAT messages, MCDW summaries, and updates from the Bureau of Meteorology. Ad-hoc collections of stations were also included after quality control checks. The observations were used to create monthly databases for seven variables: Mean, Minimum and Maximum Temperatures, Precipitation, Vapour Pressure, Wet Days, and Cloud Cover. The coverage of these variables at selected dates is shown in Figure 1 and Supplementary File 1. The dataset also includes derived variables such as Potential Evapotranspiration (PET). The data files are available in both NetCDF and space-separated ASCII text formats to maximize accessibility for users. The dataset can be accessed from the Centre for Environmental Data Analysis (CEDA) and the CRU website.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from meteorological stations.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- Meteorological station databases
- Fortran-77 programs
- ASCII text files
- Space-separated fields
- Anomaly program
- Interpolation program
- Synthetic VAP program
- Synthetic WET program
- Synthetic CLD program
- Absolutes program
- Synthetic FRS program
- Synthetic PET program
- Output process
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the data involves several steps. 

1. Anomaly production: This step produces monthly data files that list the station anomalies for each month. Station metadata is included in these files. Additionally, two files are produced for the interpolation process: one file lists the stations and their grid bounds, and the other file lists the coordinates and distances of all grid cells within the station's influence.

2. Synthetic VAP production: This step produces monthly data files that list the synthetic anomalies for each month. Station metadata is included in these files. These files are used by the interpolation process.

3. Synthetic WET production: This step produces monthly data files that list the station absolutes for each month. Station metadata is included in these files. The format of these files is identical to the format used for observations, and they are read by the anomaly process.

4. Synthetic CLD production: This step produces monthly data files that list the station anomalies for each month. Station metadata is included in these files. The format of these files is compatible with the anomaly files produced by the anomaly process, and they are used by the interpolation process.

5. Interpolation: This step produces monthly gridded data files that contain the gridded anomalies for each month. These files are used by the absolutes process.

6. Production of absolutes: This step reads the gridded anomaly files from the interpolation process and converts them to absolutes using the appropriate climatology. Monthly gridded files are produced and used by the output process.

7. Synthetic FRS production: This step reads the monthly gridded TMN absolutes produced by the absolute process and produces monthly files of FRS in the same format. These files are read by the output process.

8. Synthetic PET production: This step reads the monthly gridded TMP, TMN, TMX, VAP, and CLD absolutes produced by the absolute process and produces monthly files of PET in the same format. These files are read by the output process.

9. Output process: This step reads the gridded absolute files produced by the absolute process and the station count files produced by the interpolation process. It produces the final output files described in the 'External data records' subsection of 'Data records'.

Overall, the annotation process involves producing anomaly and absolute files for different variables, performing interpolation, and generating final output files.

uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset are for computer-aided segmentation and for code availability.
uses_ml_approach: Yes, the dataset has been tested using a machine learning approach. The gradient boosting algorithm was used for voxel-level multi-label classification, and decision trees were trained as weak learners. The algorithm was terminated after 100 iterations. Additionally, a gradient boosting machine was trained using both LGG and GBM training data in a 54-fold cross-validation setting.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No, the data of the dataset does not represent people. The data represents radiological scans and imaging sequences.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The dataset consists of pre-operative multimodal scans of glioma collections.
uses_data:
The collected data consists of pre-operative multimodal scans of glioma collections from the TCGA-GBM and TCGA-LGG datasets. These scans were obtained from the publicly available TCIA repository. The data includes pre-operative baseline reoriented, co-registered, and skull-stripped mMRI scans in NIfTI format. The dataset also includes computer-aided and manually-revised segmentation labels. Additionally, the file containers have been enriched with radiomic features to facilitate radiogenomic research and comparison of segmentation methods. 

A subset of the pre-operative scans included in the dataset was also part of the BraTS'15 dataset. These scans were skull-stripped, coregistered to the same anatomical template, and resampled to 1 mm3 voxel resolution. The identical MRI volumes as provided by the BraTS'15 challenge are included in the dataset, allowing for comparison of segmentation labels to the leaderboard of the BraTS'15 challenge. The manually-revised segmentation labels provided in the dataset are also included in the datasets of the BraTS'17 challenge, allowing for benchmarking of computational segmentation algorithms against expert-validated tumor delineation.

The complete radiological data of the TCGA-GBM and TCGA-LGG collections consist of 262 and 199 mMRI scans, respectively. These scans were provided by multiple institutions. The subset of scans included in this study consists of 135 pre-operative baseline scans from the TCIA-GBM collection and 108 pre-operative baseline scans from the TCIA-LGG collection. The scans include MRI modalities of T1-weighted pre-contrast, T1-weighted post-contrast, T2, and T2-FLAIR.

The diversity of the imaging sequences used in this study is described in detail in Table 2. This table includes information on the TCIA institutional identifier, patient information, scanner information, and specific imaging volume information extracted from the dicom headers.

The data collection process involved the identification of pre-operative baseline scans by an expert board-certified neuroradiologist. The scans were identified based on radiological assessment and the absence of clear evidence of prior instrumentation. A subset of scans from the TCIA-GBM and TCIA-LGG datasets were also included in the BraTS'15 challenge, and the radiological assessment was conducted blind to whether a scan was part of the challenge. Only the BraTS'15 volumes identified as pre-operative were included in the dataset.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from two collections, TCGA-GBM and TCGA-LGG, which consisted of 262 and 199 mMRI scans, respectively. These scans were provided by 8 and 5 institutions. The dataset includes pre-operative baseline scans with available MRI modalities of at least T1-weighted pre-contrast (T1), T1-weighted post-contrast (T1-Gd), T2, and T2-FLAIR. A total of 135 pre-operative baseline scans from the TCIA-GBM collection and 108 pre-operative baseline scans from the TCIA-LGG collection were considered for this study. 

The diversity of the imaging sequences used in this study is described in Table 2, which includes information such as the TCIA institutional identifier, patient information (age, sex, weight), scanner information (manufacturer, model, magnetic field strength, station name), and specific imaging volume information extracted from the dicom headers (modality name, series number, accession number, acquisition/study/series date, scan sequence, type, slice thickness, slice spacing, repetition time, echo time, inversion time, imaging frequency, flip angle, specific absorption rate, numbers of slices, pixel dimensions, acquisition matrix rows/columns). 

It should be noted that the diversity of the available scans in NCI/NIH/TCIA is due to the fact that TCIA collected all available scans for subjects whose tissue specimens had passed the quality evaluation of the NCI/NIH/TCGA program. The MRI scans in this collection are considered 'standard-of-care' and were not obtained following a uniform imaging protocol.

The pre-operative multimodal scans of the TCGA-GBM and TCGA-LGG glioma collections were selected from the publicly available TCIA repository. The generated data, including reoriented, co-registered, and skull-stripped mMRI scans, along with their corresponding computer-aided and manually-revised segmentation labels in NIfTI format, are made publicly available through TCIA's Analysis Results Directory. The file containers have been enriched to include an extensive panel of radiomic features, which may facilitate radiogenomic research using the TCGA portal and comparison of segmentation methods.

A subset of the pre-operative scans included in the generated data was also part of the BraTS'15 dataset. These scans were skull-stripped, coregistered to the same anatomical template, and resampled to 1 mm voxel resolution by the challenge organizers. The identical MRI volumes as provided by the BraTS'15 challenge are included in the generated data, allowing other researchers to compare their segmentation labels to the leaderboard of the BraTS'15 challenge. The manually-revised segmentation labels provided in the generated data are also included in the datasets of the BraTS'17 challenge, allowing for benchmarking computational segmentation algorithms against tumor delineation validated by expert neuroradiologists.

The segmentation labels in the dataset were produced using the GLISTRboost method, which was ranked as the best performing method and awarded the 1st prize during the International Multimodal Brain Tumor Image Segmentation challenge 2015 (BraTS'15). The authors of the paper contributed to the development of the segmentation method, correction of segmentation labels, extraction of radiomic features, and revision of the manuscript. Other contributors to the study included individuals who provided initializations for the automated segmentation method, evaluated the manually-revised segmentation labels, pre-processed the images, created metadata tables, quality checked the final provided data, and supervised the study.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an external team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the TCGA-GBM and TCGA-LGG collections, as well as from the TCIA repository.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- MRI scanners from various manufacturers and models
- FMRIB Software Library (FSL) for skull-stripping (BET) and co-registration (FLIRT)
- Multi-Atlas Skull-Stripping (MASS) and MUSE for further skull-stripping approaches
- CaPTk toolkit for pre-processing, initialization, and generation of segmentation labels
- Python package scikit-learn for the implementation of the gradient boosting algorithm
- Online Image Processing Portal (IPP) of the CBICA for the segmentation approach (GLISTRboost)
- TCIA repository for accessing the pre-operative multimodal scans
- NIfTI format for storing the scans and segmentation labels
- Brain Extraction Tool (BET) from FSL for skull-stripping
- Multi-atlas registration and label fusion framework for automated skull-stripping
- Smallest Univalue Segment Assimilating Nucleus (SUSAN) for smoothing the volumes
- ITK (HistogramMatchingImageFilter) for matching intensity histograms
annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the data involved the use of a segmentation method called GLISTRboost. This method was ranked as the best performing method and awarded the 1st prize during the International Multimodal Brain Tumor Image Segmentation challenge in 2015. The authors of the study conceived the study, provided initializations for the automated segmentation method, corrected segmentation labels, extracted radiomic features, and wrote the manuscript. They were assisted by other individuals who provided initializations for the automated segmentation method, corrected segmentation labels, extracted radiomic features, and revised the manuscript. The segmentation labels used in the study delineate the enhancing part of the tumor core (ET), the non-enhancing part of the tumor core (NET), and the peritumoral edema (ED). The manual correction of the segmentation labels involved correcting mislabeled voxels according to the rules set by an expert board-certified neuroradiologist. The corrected labels were iteratively re-evaluated by the neuroradiologist until they were satisfactory segmented.
annotation_team_type: The data was annotated by an internal team, which included the authors of the study and other individuals who provided initializations for the automated segmentation method, corrected segmentation labels, extracted radiomic features, and revised the manuscript. The manual correction of the segmentation labels was done by an expert board-certified neuroradiologist.
annotation_infrastructure: Yes, the tools or infrastructures used during the annotation process are GLISTRboost, BET, FLIRT, FSL, MASS, MUSE, CaPTk, SUSAN, scikit-learn.
column122: No. The context does not provide demographic information about the team who annotate the data.

They also mention that the data can be regarded as anonymized to the best of their knowledge.
uses_data: The collected data in the HAM10000 dataset consists of a large collection of multi-source dermatoscopic images of common pigmented skin lesions. The dataset includes images and metadata, which are accessible at the public ISIC-archive through the archive gallery as well as through standardized API-calls. The dataset is deposited at the Harvard Dataverse, and a summary of the number of images in the training-set according to diagnosis is provided in Table 1. The dataset workup methods involved organizing and cleaning the data, with final images being standardized and stored in a common format. Manual correction was also performed on scanned diapositives to improve image quality. Illuminant color estimation was done using a grey-world assumption in Lab-color space. The dataset also includes examples of lesions taken at different magnifications and angles. Custom generated code for the described methods is available on GitHub.
collection_explanation:
The dataset, HAM10000, was collected over a period of 20 years from two different sites: the Department of Dermatology at the Medical University of Vienna, Austria, and the skin cancer practice of Cliff Rosendahl in Queensland, Australia. The Australian site stored images and metadata in PowerPoint files and Excel databases, while the Austrian site stored images and metadata in different formats during different time periods.

The dataset workup methods involved organizing and cleaning the data from different sources. The images and data content were entered into a pipeline, and the final images were standardized and stored in a common format. Figure 1 in the document provides a schematic flow of these workup methods.

Figure 2 in the document shows an example of manual correction of a scanned diapositive. The original scanned image had remaining black border, off-center lesion, yellow hue, and reduced luminance. After manual quality review, the final image was obtained.

Figure 3 in the document demonstrates the estimation of illuminant color of the dataset. The values were estimated with a grey-world assumption of all training-set images in Lab-color space before and after manual histogram changes.

Figure 4 in the document presents an example triplet of the same lesion. These images were originally taken at different magnifications and angles, rather than being cropped to different sizes of a large source image.

Table 1 in the document provides a summary of the number of images in the HAM10000 training-set according to diagnosis, in comparison to existing databases. All data records of the HAM10000 dataset are deposited at the Harvard Dataverse, and the images and metadata are also accessible at the public ISIC-archive through the archive gallery as well as through standardized API-calls.

annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the data involved several steps. P.T., C.R., and H.K. were involved in writing the Data Descriptor and performing various tasks such as data handling, image processing and analysis, expert annotation, and quality review. The images in the dataset were subjected to random transformations to serve as data augmentation and to visualize both general and local features. Insufficiently magnified images of small lesions or out-of-focus images were removed. The data was anonymized by using automated screening by neural networks, multiple manual reviews, and clearing EXIF-data to remove any potentially identifiable information. The data collection was approved by the ethics review committee at the Medical University of Vienna and the University of Queensland.

The dataset is a global monthly high-resolution climate dataset called TerraClimate, which includes variables for calculating energy-based reference potential evapotranspiration and a water balance model. The data was developed by downscaling coarser resolution temporal anomalies from climate research unit time series data and the Japanese 55-year reanalysis using climatic aided interpolation. uses_data:
The collected data is a global monthly high-resolution climate dataset called TerraClimate. It covers the period from 1958 to 2015 and includes variables for calculating energy-based reference potential evapotranspiration and a water balance model. The dataset was developed by downscaling coarser resolution temporal anomalies from the Climate Research Unit time series data version 4.0 (CRU Ts4.0) and the Japanese 55-year Reanalysis (JRA-55) using climatic aided interpolation. The procedures for developing the monthly water balance dataset for the same period are also discussed. 

To validate the TerraClimate product, a validation was conducted using station-based data obtained from the Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN) database. The validation focused on monthly temperature and precipitation data. The temperature data used was corrected for climate inhomogeneities, while the precipitation data was obtained from the GHCNv2 dataset. The validation was constrained to GHCN stations that had complete monthly data for at least 30 calendar years from 1958-2015. A total of 3,230 stations were used for temperature validation and 6,102 stations for precipitation validation. It should be noted that many of these stations were used in both the WorldClim and CRU datasets, which may affect the independence of the comparison. Data from TerraClimate were extracted at grid cells co-located with individual stations.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected by extracting data from the TerraClimate product, which provides monthly temperature and precipitation data. The validation of the TerraClimate product was conducted using station-based data obtained from the Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN) database. The temperature data used in the validation were corrected for climate inhomogeneities that arise due to non-climatic artifacts, such as station relocation or observational practice, from the GHCNv3 dataset. The monthly precipitation data used in the validation were obtained from the GHCNv2 dataset.

The validation was constrained to GHCN stations that had complete monthly data for at least 30 calendar years from 1958-2015. This resulted in a total of 3,230 stations for temperature and 6,102 stations for precipitation. It should be noted that many of these stations were used in both the WorldClim and CRU datasets, which means that the comparison between TerraClimate and these datasets is not completely independent.

Data from TerraClimate were extracted at grid cells that were co-located with individual stations. The dataset includes variables for calculating energy-based reference potential evapotranspiration and a water balance model. The procedures for downscaling coarser resolution temporal anomalies from the CRU Ts4.0 and JRA-55 datasets using climatic aided interpolation are discussed in the paper. The procedures for developing the monthly water balance dataset for the period 1958-2015 are also discussed.

In addition to the collection process, the paper also provides information about the author contributions and the background and summary of the research.

The tools, devices, or infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. Climate Research Unit time series data version 4.0 (CRU Ts4.0)
2. Japanese 55-year Reanalysis (JRA-55)
3. WorldClim 11,15 (for high-resolution climatological fields)
4. Climatic aided interpolation
5. Global Historical Climatology Network (GHCN) database
6. NetCDF format for data storage and distribution
7. University of Idaho's Northwest Knowledge Network for hosting the data repository.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves comparing the TerraClimate dataset to the CRU Ts4.0 dataset for a specific region in northwestern North America in 2015. The authors highlight the spatial detail added by the TerraClimate dataset compared to CRU Ts4.0, particularly in terms of energy and moisture gradients, average maximum temperature, annual precipitation totals, annual climatic water deficit, and annual Q in 2015. The authors also mention that the use of climate data has increased in recent years due to the availability of data, broadening of disciplines using such data, and increased interest in assessing local impacts from climate change. The technical validation of the data includes comparing cumulative water-year precipitation data to observed Q for each watershed and finding that the WBM runoff data explains more variance in interannual variability in Q compared to using precipitation data alone. The authors also note the challenges of interpolating estimates of precipitation data, particularly in mountainous watersheds, and the need for continued improvement in mapping climate at fine spatial scales and investment in observational systems in data sparse regions.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of atomic coordinates and calculated properties for a set of molecules. Each molecule is stored in a file named dataset_index.xyz, using the XYZ format. This format includes a header line specifying the number of atoms, a comment line, and lines containing the element type and atomic coordinates for each atom. The properties are stored in a specific order, as indicated in Table 2 and Table 3 of the paper.

To ensure the accuracy of the data, a consistency check was performed using the InChI strings obtained from the initial Cartesian coordinates. Some molecules did not pass this test due to the fact that SMILES and InChI representations are not unique. Small differences in interatomic distances, bond angles, and dihedral angles can lead to different molecular graphs encoded by the string. The distribution of Coulomb-matrix distances between Corina generated Cartesian coordinates and B3LYP coordinates was analyzed for the molecules that failed the consistency check.

Additionally, the quantum chemistry results were validated using the B3LYP/6-31G(2df,p) based DFT method. Benchmark calculations were performed for a subset of 100 randomly selected molecules using high-level theories G4MP2, G4, and CBS-QB3. The G4MP2 method, known for its predictive power, was compared to experimental data and showed a mean absolute error (MAE) of 1.0 kcal/mol and a root mean square error (RMSE) of 1.5 kcal/mol. The B3LYP method was found to have a mean absolute error of no more than 5 kcal/mol for the heats of atomization of the 100 molecules.

Overall, the collected data includes atomic coordinates, calculated properties, and validation of the quantum chemistry results using the B3LYP/6-31G(2df,p) based DFT method.
collection_explanation:
The collection process of the dataset involved several steps. First, the authors obtained trial licenses for the MOPAC and Corina packages from James Stewart and Christof H. Schwab, respectively. These packages were used for calculations and generating Cartesian coordinates for the molecules.

The authors also used the GDB-17 data provided by J.-L. Reymond and his group. This data was used for extensive discussions and ideas during the research.

The dataset was stored in a file format called XYZ. This format includes atomic coordinates and calculated properties for each molecule. The format consists of a header line specifying the number of atoms, a comment line, and lines containing element type and atomic coordinates for each atom.

To ensure the consistency of the dataset, the authors compared the IUPAC International Chemical Identifier (InChI) strings obtained from the Cartesian coordinates generated by Corina with the original GDB-17 SMILES strings. They found that some molecules did not pass this consistency check due to implementation-specific artifacts in the transformation of Cartesian coordinates to string-based chemical identifiers.

To quantify this artifact, the authors calculated the distribution of Coulomb-matrix distances between the Corina-generated Cartesian coordinates and B3LYP coordinates for the molecules that failed the consistency check. They found that molecules with small Coulomb-matrix distances had minor differences in interatomic distances, bond angles, and dihedral angles, while molecules with large distances had significant alterations and rearrangements of covalent bonding patterns.

It is worth noting that all the constitutional isomers of C7H10O2 that underwent G4MP2 calculations passed the geometry consistency check.

Overall, the dataset collection process involved obtaining trial licenses for software packages, using GDB-17 data for discussions and ideas, generating Cartesian coordinates, comparing InChI and SMILES strings for consistency, and quantifying the artifacts in the transformation of Cartesian coordinates to chemical identifiers.

collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, or infrastructure used during the collection process include MOPAC and Corina packages for quantum chemistry calculations, CPU time at the Universitätsrechenzentrum, University of Basel, and resources of the Argonne Leadership Computing Facility at Argonne National Laboratory.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several steps. First, the molecular structures and properties of the molecules are stored in a file format called XYZ, which includes atomic coordinates and calculated properties. The XYZ format contains a header line specifying the number of atoms, a comment line, and lines containing element type and atomic coordinates. 

Next, a consistency check is performed to ensure the accuracy of the molecular structures. This check involves comparing the SMILES and InChI representations of the molecules obtained from the Cartesian coordinates. If there are any discrepancies, further calculations are performed using different methods (such as PM7 and B3LYP) to obtain the correct SMILES string.

After the consistency check, quantum chemistry calculations are performed using the B3LYP/6-31G(2df,p) method. Additional benchmark calculations are also performed using high-level theories such as G4MP2, G4, and CBS-QB3 to validate the accuracy of the B3LYP calculations.

The results of these calculations, including deviations and errors, are summarized in Table 1. The mean absolute error of B3LYP heats of atomization for the 100 molecules is no more than 5 kcal/mol.

Finally, the molecular structures and properties are made publicly available on Figshare in a plain text XYZ-like format. The deposited files include the GDB-1 to GDB-9 molecules, the constitutional isomers of C7H10O2, the validation molecules, enthalpies of atomization, and atomic reference data.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1) To compare sectoral and reference approach emission inventories.
2) To analyze the uncertainties in China's fossil fuel data.
3) To calculate CO2 emissions for China using different emission factors.

It also mentions that emissions from sources other than energy-related and cement-related emissions were not taken into account.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of 1,172 data records, which include emission and energy inventories. The project was led by Y.S., who collected and assembled the data and prepared the manuscript. D.G. designed the research, while H.Z. collected the raw data. J.O., Y.L., J.M., Z.M., Z.L., and Q.Z. revised the manuscript and participated in the construction of the database.

The dataset includes sectoral-and reference-approach emission inventories. Emissions calculated based on the IPCC and UN-average emissions factors are 10% larger than the upper bound of the 97.5% confidential interval due to their high emission factor value. On the other hand, emissions calculated based on the emission factors from Liu et al.'s nature, NC1994, and MEIC have relatively low values. Additionally, emissions calculated based on provincial aggregated energy data are about 5% higher than those based on national data due to the difference in the national and provincial data.

There are uncertainties in the dataset that should be considered when using it. These uncertainties include "lack of completeness," "lack of data," and "measurement error." Although these uncertainties are small and difficult to quantify, they are essential parts of the inventories' uncertainties. It is important to note that the dataset only considers energy-related emissions and cement-related emissions. Emissions from other sources such as agriculture, land-use change and forestry, waste, and other industrial processes were not taken into account.

The dataset also includes energy-related sectoral approach emissions. The emission factors of coal-related and oil-related fuels were updated using the ratio of raw coal and crude oil, respectively. Different oxygenation efficiencies were adopted for fossil fuels used in different sectors to represent the different combustion technology levels of the sectors. The emission inventories were constructed using MATLAB R2014a with sectoral fossil fuel consumption and emission factors. The code used for constructing the inventories is provided in the Supplementary Information. Additionally, the dataset includes the formatted energy data of China and its provinces for additional data transparency and verifiability. Researchers can use the MATLAB code and energy inventories to recalculate the CO2 emissions for China by adopting different emission factors.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected and assembled by Y.S., who led the project. The raw data was collected by H.Z. The research was designed by D.G. The manuscript was prepared by Y.S. and revised by J.O., Y.L., J.M., Z.M., Z.L., and Q.Z. The dataset contains a total of 1,172 data records, which include emission and energy inventories.

The dataset includes sectoral-and reference-approach emission inventories. Emissions were calculated based on different emission factors, such as those from the IPCC, UN-average, Liu et al.'s nature, NC1994, and MEIC. Emissions calculated based on the IPCC and UN-average emissions factors were found to be 10% larger than the upper bound of the 97.5% confidential interval due to their high emission factor value. On the other hand, emissions calculated based on the emission factors from Liu et al.'s nature, NC1994, and MEIC had relatively low values.

There is also a difference in emissions calculated based on national and provincial aggregated energy data. Emissions calculated based on provincial data were about 5% higher than those based on national data. This difference is attributed to the variation in the national and provincial data.

The dataset has some uncertainties that should be considered when using it. These uncertainties include "lack of completeness," "lack of data," and "measurement error." Although these uncertainties are small and difficult to quantify, they are essential parts of the inventories' uncertainties.

It is important to note that the dataset only considers energy-related emissions and cement-related emissions. Emissions from other sources, such as agriculture, land-use change and forestry, waste, and other industrial processes, were not taken into account.

The CO2 emission inventories in the dataset are constructed in a uniform format. The sectoral approach inventories are matrices with 19 columns and 47 rows. The 19 columns represent 17 fossil fuel-related emissions, cement-related emissions, and total emissions. The 47 rows represent the 47 socioeconomic sectors. Each element of the matrices represents the CO2 emissions from fossil fuel combustion/cement production in the corresponding sector.

The dataset also includes reference emission inventories in a uniform format. These inventories provide provincial-level data for reference. The sectoral and reference approach inventories include emissions from every individual item, such as production and import, of the three primary energy sources and the cement process.

Overall, the dataset provides comprehensive information on CO2 emissions in China, including sectoral breakdowns and reference inventories.

The manuscript was revised and the database was constructed by J.O., Y.L., J.M., Z.M., Z.L., and Q.Z. The data records consist of 1,172 emission and energy inventories. The emissions were calculated using different approaches and factors, such as IPCC and UN-average emissions factors, Liu et al.'s nature, NC1994, and MEIC emission factors. The emissions calculated based on IPCC and UN-average emissions factors were found to be 10% larger than the upper bound of the 97.5% confidential interval. The emissions calculated based on provincial aggregated energy data were about 5% higher than those based on national data. The datasets have uncertainties related to emission factors, fossil fuel data, lack of completeness, lack of data, and measurement error. The datasets only considered energy-related emissions and cement-related emissions, excluding emissions from other sources such as agriculture, land-use change and forestry, waste, and other industrial processes.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
- Fundamental and application-related studies of inorganic compounds.
- Materials discovery and design, in the search for and optimization of materials with targeted mechanical and thermal properties.
- Querying existing compounds from the database by specifying desired elastic properties.
- Data mining and machine learning to reveal fundamental trends in the elastic properties of compounds and guide the screening of potentially interesting materials for target properties.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are materials, not humans.
uses_data:
The collected data consists of elastic property data and related metadata for 1,181 materials. The data set is stored as individual JSON documents, which provide a readily parsable and human-readable solution for data exchange. The metadata for each material includes descriptions of the material's structure, structure symmetry, and calculation parameters such as k-points density. The JSON keys for the metadata are listed in Table 2 of the paper.

The structure of each material is presented in both Crystallographic Information File (cif) and poscar-format. The poscar-format is the standard structure description used by the VASP-code.

The data set is publicly available at the Materials Project website and can be downloaded as a JSON file or accessed via the Materials Project REST API. The website also provides a web interface that allows users to search for materials with specific properties by querying the elastic constant database. The materials detail pages on the website now include calculated elasticity data when available.

The authors anticipate that this dataset, along with the provided methods for querying it, will be a valuable tool for fundamental and application-related studies of inorganic compounds. It is expected to be particularly useful for materials discovery and design, as well as for efforts aimed at optimizing materials with targeted mechanical and thermal properties. Researchers will be able to query existing compounds from the database by specifying desired elastic properties, and future extensions of this work will include a web interface where users can calculate elastic properties on demand by uploading a file describing the crystallography of the material of interest. Data mining and machine learning techniques can be applied to reveal fundamental trends in the elastic properties of compounds and guide the screening of potentially interesting materials.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected by storing each material as an individual JSON document. The JSON format was chosen because it is easily parsed by computers and also readable by humans. Each JSON document contains key/value pairs that describe the material, such as its structure and structure symmetry, as well as calculation parameters like k-points density. The metadata keys and their descriptions are listed in Table 2. The structure of each material is presented in both Crystallographic Information File (cif) and poscar-format, with the poscar-format being the standard structure description used by the VASP-code.

The dataset was obtained from the Dryad Digital Repository, with the data citation provided as De Jong et al., 2015. This dataset is the largest collection of consistently calculated or measured elastic tensors for crystalline inorganic materials to date. It is expected to be a valuable resource for fundamental and application-related studies of inorganic compounds, particularly in materials discovery and design. Researchers can query the database by specifying desired elastic properties, such as a maximum value of the shear modulus with minimum elastic anisotropy. For compounds that are not currently in the database, future extensions of this work will include a web interface where users can calculate elastic properties by uploading a file describing the crystallography of the material. Data mining and machine learning techniques can be applied to uncover trends in the elastic properties of compounds and guide the screening of materials with target properties.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Materials Project (MP) infrastructure.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- JSON format for storing the data set
- Crystallographic Information File (cif) and poscar-format for presenting the structure
- VASP-code for standard structure description
- MP HT calculation infrastructure for data generation
- DFT-calculation for tighter structural relaxation
- Stress-strain method for calculating elastic constants
- Data mining and machine learning techniques for analyzing the data and revealing trends
annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the data involves storing and reporting the results for mechanically unstable compounds on the website, but with a warning message to the user. Elastic tensors that have achieved sufficient numerical convergence are inserted into the MP database and reported on the website. A JSON data document is generated for each reported elastic tensor, which is publicly available at the Dryad-repository. The structure generation and data analysis for elastic constant calculations are performed using the open-source materials analysis code pymatgen. The workflow software FireWorks is used to automate the high-throughput calculations and data management.

uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is deidentified and includes vital sign measurements, care plan documentation, severity of illness measures, diagnosis information, treatment information, and more. However, personal information such as personal numbers, addresses, dates, and ages over 89 have been removed to protect privacy. The dataset is focused on the data collected for critically ill patients in intensive care units.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected in the eICU Collaborative Research Database includes vital signs, laboratory measurements, medications, APACHE components, care plan information, admission diagnosis, patient history, time-stamped diagnoses, and chosen treatments. It does not specify that the subjects of the collection process are humans.
uses_data:
The collected data in the eICU Collaborative Research Database includes vital signs, laboratory measurements, medications, APACHE components, care plan information, admission diagnosis, patient history, time-stamped diagnoses, and chosen treatments. Each patient is identified by a unique identifier (uniquePid) and may have multiple hospitalizations (patientHealthSystemStayId) and unit stays (patientUnitStayId). The data is organized into tables that correspond to the type of data contained within each table.

The database structure consists of comma-separated value (CSV) files that can be loaded into any relational database system. Each file represents a single table, and references to tables are denoted using italicized font, while references to columns are denoted using monospace font. All tables in the database are deidentified to meet the safe harbor provision of the US Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA). This means that all protected health information (PHI), such as personal numbers, addresses, and dates, has been removed. Patient identifiers in the dataset cannot be linked back to the original identifiable data, and hospital and ICU identifiers have also been removed to protect privacy.

The database schema was established in collaboration with Privacert, who certified the reidentification risk as meeting safe harbor standards. Free-text fields were scanned for personal information using a rule-based approach, and rows containing potential PHI were deleted. Additionally, large portions of all tables were manually reviewed to ensure complete deidentification.

The data were verified for integrity during the transfer process using MD5 checksums. Very little post-processing has been performed to maintain data fidelity. However, the reliability and completion of data elements may vary across hospitals and ICUs due to customized workflows and clinical documentation processes.

Data access to the eICU-CRD is available through a PhysioNet repository. Access requires proof of completion of a course on human subjects research and a data use agreement that includes restrictions on data sharing and re-identification. Future updates are planned for the dataset to address issues, add new tables, and insert additional data. The current version of eICU-CRD contains data for patients admitted between 2014-2015, and efforts will be made to ensure the data remain contemporary.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from the eICU Collaborative Research Database, which is a set of comma separated value (CSV) files that can be loaded into any relational database system. The data in the files have been deidentified to meet the safe harbor provision of the US Health Insurance Portability and Accountability Act (HIPAA). This means that all protected health information (PHI), such as personal numbers, addresses, dates, and ages over 89, has been removed. Patients were randomly assigned a unique identifier, and a lookup key was not retained, so the identifiers in the dataset cannot be linked back to the original identifiable data. Hospital and ICU identifiers have also been removed to protect the privacy of contributing institutions and providers.

The schema of the dataset is highly denormalized, with each table containing data for a single table. All tables can be accessed independently and linked to a single patient tracking table using patientUnitStayId. The only exception is the hospital table, which links to the patient table using hospitalId. Each table, other than patient and hospital, has a randomly generated primary key with the suffix 'id' to ensure uniqueness and data integrity.

To ensure data integrity, the data were verified during the transfer process using MD5 checksums. Very little post-processing has been performed to maintain data fidelity. However, it is important to note that the reliability and completion of data elements may vary across hospitals and ICUs due to customized workflows and clinical documentation processes.

The sample selection process involved identifying all hospital discharges between 2014 and 2015 and extracting a single index stay for each unique patient. A stratified random sample of patient index stays was then performed based on the proportion of index stays in each hospital from the eRI data repository. This was done to maintain the distribution of first ICU stays across the hospitals in the dataset. All subsequent stays for each selected patient were also included in the dataset, regardless of the admitting hospital. Stays in step down units or low acuity units were removed from the dataset.

The dataset was published and the paper was written collaboratively by A.E.W.J. and T.J.P. Sample selection was performed by J.D.R., who also provided documentation for the process and collaborated on the paper. L.A.C., R.G.M., and O.B. reviewed the paper and supervised the work.
