uses_data:
The collected data in this study includes various inventories and datasets related to energy consumption and CO2 emissions in China. 

First, there are two national energy inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories provide information on energy consumption at the national level.

Second, there are 60 provincial energy inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories cover all 30 provinces in China and provide detailed information on energy consumption at the provincial level.

Third, there are two national sectoral emission inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories focus on CO2 emissions and provide sector-specific data on emissions at the national level.

Fourth, there are two national reference emission inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories also focus on CO2 emissions but use a different approach than the sectoral inventories. They provide reference data on emissions at the national level.

Fifth, there are 60 provincial sectoral emission inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories provide sector-specific data on CO2 emissions at the provincial level for all 30 provinces.

Finally, there are 60 provincial reference emission inventories for the years 2016 and 2017. These inventories provide reference data on CO2 emissions at the provincial level for all 30 provinces.

In addition to these inventories, the study also includes tables that provide information on fossil fuels and emission factors, as well as economic sectors. The uncertainties associated with the data are also discussed, with a focus on activity data and emission factors. The study uses Monte Carlo simulation to propagate these uncertainties and calculate the integrated uncertainty of the entire emission inventory.

Overall, the collected data in this study provides a comprehensive picture of energy consumption and CO2 emissions in China at both the national and provincial levels.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through a multi-step process. The energy activity data, which includes production, transformation, final consumption, loss, and others, was collected from China and its provinces' Energy Balance Tables. These tables are published in the China Energy Statistical Yearbook for the years 2017 and 2018. The Energy Balance Table provides comprehensive energy flows and utilization for different sectors. The final energy consumption data in the Energy Balance Table includes eight sectors.

To expand the "Industry" sector, 40 sub-sectors were created based on the "Industry Sectoral Energy Consumption Table (ISECT)". The country-level ISECTs were collected from the China Energy Statistical Yearbook for the years 2017 and 2018, while the provincial ISECTs were collected from each province's statistical yearbooks.

For the provinces of Hebei, Shanghai, Jiangsu, Zhejiang, Shandong, Guangxi, Hainan, Sichuan, and Guizhou, which did not have ISECTs, data from previous years were used assuming their economic structure remained unchanged.

The cement production data for China in 2016 and 2017 were collected from the China Statistical Yearbook for the respective years. Provincial production data were collected from each province's statistical yearbook for 2017 and 2018.

The emission inventories were constructed based on the collected data and using emission factors and energy data from previous studies. The emission factors were estimated based on a wide investigation of 4,243 coal mine samples. It is important to note that this study only accounts for direct emissions from the consumption of 17 fossil fuels.

Overall, the dataset collection process involved gathering energy activity data from the Energy Balance Tables, expanding the "Industry" sector using ISECTs, collecting cement production data, and using emission factors from previous studies.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several steps. First, the activity data and emission factors are collected from various sources, including national and provincial energy inventories, sectoral emission inventories, and reference emission inventories. These datasets provide information on energy consumption and emission factors for different economic sectors and fossil fuels.

Next, the uncertainties in the activity data and emission factors are quantified. The activity data uncertainty is mainly due to the dual system and poor quality of energy statistics in China. The emission factors uncertainty arises from variations in different sources and publications of emission factors. Monte Carlo simulation is used to propagate these uncertainties and calculate the integrated uncertainty of the entire emission inventory.

The results of the uncertainty analysis are presented in Figure 2, which shows the uncertainty range of energy-related emissions. The uncertainties from activity data range from 1.9% to 12.8% in 2016 and from 1.9% to 12.7% in 2017. On the other hand, the uncertainties from emission factors range from -14.5% to 29.6% in 2016 and from -14.6% to 29.6% in 2017.

To validate the emission accounts, the estimates are compared with other existing emission datasets. The estimates are found to be relatively lower but very close to China's official emissions, with gaps ranging from -5.81% to 1.98%. The national sectoral emissions are lower than the official emissions for certain years, while the provincial aggregated emissions are either lower or higher than the official national emissions for different years.

The annotation process also highlights the limitations of the datasets and suggests future work to improve the accuracy of China's emission accounts. These limitations include the exclusion of other components in scope 1 direct emissions, the use of national average emission factors for provincial emissions, and the lack of sub-sectoral energy consumption data for certain provinces. Future work will focus on expanding the accounting scope, investigating regional-specific emission factors, and obtaining updated sectoral energy data for the provinces.

Overall, the annotation process involves collecting data, quantifying uncertainties, validating the estimates, and identifying limitations and areas for improvement.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of two components: a time series file (covid-testing-all-observations.csv) and metadata (covid-testing-source-details.csv). The metadata table provides source details for each country-series, where the combination of Country and Series fields creates a unique ID. The time series file contains cumulative and daily testing data for each country-series. The raw data collected from the source is also provided (raw-collected-data.csv) to show how the time series data is constructed from the original observations. Additionally, the United Nations population data for 2020 (un-2020-population.csv) is included to calculate per capita measures in the time series.

The database includes two parts for each country: (1) a time series for the cumulative and daily number of tests performed or people tested, along with derived variables; (2) metadata that describes the source and provides information on data quality or comparability issues. Most countries have a single time series, either for the number of people tested or the number of tests performed. For a few countries, both series are provided, and metadata is provided for each separate series.

The fields in the database include:
- Cumulative total: The reported cumulative amount of testing as of a specific date. The date to which the cumulative figures date back to, if known, is provided in the metadata. In cases where only daily testing figures are available, this field is derived as the running total of the raw daily data. It is also provided per thousand people of the country's 2020 population.
- Daily change in cumulative total: This field represents the number of new tests or people tested per day.

The fields common to both the time series file and the raw data file include:
- Date: This field indicates the date on which samples were taken, analyzed, or registered, or the date they were included in official figures. Sources aim to provide testing data related to a specific, stable cut-off time each day. Any significant changes in reporting windows are noted in the Notes field.
- Series: Multiple series, such as people tested and samples tested, are included for some countries and are identified by this field.

It is important to note that the latest data in the database for each country may not refer to the date the database was updated, as countries update their testing data at different frequencies.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected using a combination of manual and automated methods. The collection process varied by country and can be categorized into three categories. 

Firstly, for some countries, the figures reported in official sources such as press releases, government websites, dedicated dashboards, and social media accounts of national authorities were recorded manually as they were released. 

Secondly, for countries where the publications were released in a regular, machine-readable format or where structured data was published at a stable location, the data collection was automated using R and Python scripts that were executed daily. These scripts were regularly audited for technical bugs by comparing their output against the original official sources. 

Lastly, in cases where manual collection was difficult, data was sourced from non-official groups collecting the official data, often on GitHub. These data sources were also regularly audited for accuracy against the original official sources. 

Detailed metadata for each series was manually gathered and summarized, guided by a checklist of data quality questions. 

The database consists of two components: a time series file (covid-testing-all-observations.csv) including observations of cumulative and daily testing, and metadata (covid-testing-source-details.csv). The metadata table provides source details for each country-series, where the combination of Country and Series fields make up a unique ID. The time series data for cumulative and daily testing for each country-series is provided in the covid-testing-all-observations.csv file. 

The raw data collected from the sources is also provided (raw-collected-data.csv) to show how the time series data is constructed from the original observations. Additionally, the United Nations population data for 2020 (un-2020-population.csv) is included to derive per capita measures in the time series. 

For each included country, the database provides a time series for the cumulative and daily number of tests performed or people tested, along with derived variables. Metadata is also provided, which includes a detailed description of the source and any available information on data quality or comparability issues. In cases where both the number of people tested and the number of tests performed are available, separate series and metadata are provided for each. 

The fields in the dataset include Date, Series, and Cumulative total. The Date field represents the date on which samples were taken, analyzed, or registered, or the date they were included in official figures. The Series field indicates the type of series (e.g., people tested and samples tested) for some countries. The Cumulative total field represents the cumulative total of tests performed or people tested.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process for the data involves several steps. First, the authors of the database, including Joe Hasell, Edouard Mathieu, Hannah Ritchie, Diana Beltekian, Charlie Giattino, Bobbie Macdonald, Esteban Ortiz-Ospina, and Max Roser, coordinate and manage the database. They also conduct background research and provide editorial oversight.

The data is collected from various sources, primarily official sources. The documentation provided by these sources is used to interpret and compare the data with other countries. The database aims to include any relevant information provided by the original source.

The database consists of two parts for each country: a time series for the cumulative and daily number of tests performed or people tested, and metadata. The metadata includes a detailed description of the source and any available information on data quality or comparability issues.

The database covers observations for 94 countries, representing 69% of the world's population. However, the coverage may be lower for more recent periods due to differences in the frequency of publishing testing data.

Overall, the annotation process involves collecting data, verifying its accuracy, and providing relevant information for interpretation and comparison.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Technical validation and confirmation of accuracy of draft genomes for specific downstream purposes.
2. Binning and analysis of secondary contigs for generating draft genomes and assessing completion and contamination estimates.
3. Gathering metagenomic sequences and assembly of samples from different oceanic provinces.
4. Independent assessment of the accuracy of genes, contigs, and phylogenetic assignments for organisms of interest.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: Yes, the context mentions that the TOBG genomes have been generated using an automated process without manual assessment, and therefore, all downstream research should independently assess the accuracy of genes, contigs, and phylogenetic assignments for organisms of interest.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset consists of metagenomic sequences collected from various samples and stations during the Tara Oceans expedition.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The collected data consists of metagenomic sequences obtained from samples collected during the Tara Oceans expedition.
uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of metagenomic sequences obtained from 234 samples collected from 61 stations during the Tara Oceans expedition. These samples were collected from different size fractions (viral, girus, bacterial, and protistan) and at various depths (surface, deep chlorophyll maximum, and mesopelagic) at each station. The metagenomic sequences were accessed from the European Molecular Biology Laboratory-European Bioinformatics Institute (EMBL-EBI).

Each sample was individually assembled using the Megahit software, with a specific parameter setting (--preset meta-sensitive). In cases where the size of the samples from the South Pacific was too large for assembly, the samples were split to allow successful assembly. The assembly was done individually for each sample to avoid unresolvable assembly branches caused by strain heterogeneity in closely related organisms. However, this approach does not resolve issues with abundant organisms that have high degrees of strain heterogeneity within a single sample.

In total, over 102 billion paired-end reads were assembled into more than 562 million contigs. Contigs less than 2 kb in length were not used in downstream analysis. To reduce the computational load, primary contigs with at least 99% semi-global identity were combined using CD-HIT-EST software. The combined contigs from the same oceanographic province were then co-assembled using Minimus2 software. This resulted in approximately 7.2 million secondary contigs for downstream analysis.

The dataset also includes information on the number of secondary contigs generated for each province, the number of contigs binned, the corresponding length cutoff, and the number of draft genomes reconstructed. This information is provided in Table 2 of the document.

Figure 1 of the document shows a map depicting the approximate locations of the Tara Oceans sampling stations, which were grouped into larger provinces based on Longhurst Provinces and site proximity. The abbreviations used for draft genome IDs correspond to the provinces.

Figure 2 of the document shows a maximum likelihood tree of the draft genomes based on 16 concatenated single-copy phylogenetic markers. The tree includes bootstrap values, with values greater than 0.75 shown. The circle size representing the bootstrap value is scaled from 0.75 to 1.0. Nodes with an average branch length distance less than 0.5 were collapsed, and the number of draft genomes in each node is provided. The tree was generated using the Interactive Tree of Life (iTOL) software.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected as part of the Tara Oceans expedition, where metagenomic sequences were gathered from 234 samples collected at 61 stations. These samples were collected from different size fractions (viral, girus, bacterial, and protistan) and at various depths (surface, deep chlorophyll maximum, and mesopelagic) at each station. The metagenomic sequences were accessed from the European Molecular Biology Laboratory-European Bioinformatics Institute (EMBL-EBI). Each sample was individually assembled using Megahit, and over 102 billion paired-end reads were assembled into more than 562 million contigs. Contigs less than 2 kb in length were not used in downstream analysis. The primary contigs from each oceanographic province were then processed using CD-HIT-EST to reduce computational load, and the contigs were co-assembled using Minimus2. This resulted in approximately 7.2 million secondary contigs for downstream analysis.

Binning of the metagenomic reads was performed using a custom BinSanity workflow. The reads from each sample in an oceanic province were recruited against the secondary contigs generated from that same province. Coverage values for each contig from each sample were determined using BinSanity-profile. The coverage values were log normalized and multiplied by 100. The secondary contigs were size selected to choose approximately 100,000 contigs for binning. Binning was performed iteratively six times using BinSanity, with changes to the preference value after the first three iterations. Bins with high contamination and low completion were processed with the BinSanity-refinement script. After each iteration of binning, bins were assessed using CheckM for completion and contamination estimates. Bins that met certain criteria for completion and contamination were reclassified as draft genomes. In total, 2,631 draft genomes were generated, with 1,491 genomes being more than 70% complete and 420 genomes meeting a high-quality threshold of more than 90% complete and less than 5% contamination. An additional 15,557 bins were generated that did not meet the criteria for reclassification as draft genomes. These bins may offer pertinent information for different downstream analyses.

annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involved two main steps: binning and phylogenetic assignment.

Binning: The metagenomic reads from each sample in an oceanic province were recruited against the set of secondary contigs generated from that same province. Binning was performed using a custom BinSanity workflow. Coverage values were determined for each contig from each sample using BinSanity-profile. The coverage values were log normalized and size selected to choose approximately 100,000 contigs for binning. Bins with high contamination and low completion were processed with the BinSanity-refinement script. After each binning step, bins were assessed using CheckM for completion and contamination estimates. Bins that met certain criteria were considered draft genomes, while others were combined for the next iteration of binning.

Phylogenetic assignment: Putative coding DNA sequences (CDSs) were predicted for all secondary contigs. These contigs, along with complete and partial reference genomes, were searched for phylogenetic markers using hidden Markov models (HMMs) collected from the Pfam database. Two sets of single-copy markers were used to construct phylogenetic trees. Draft and reference genomes were required to possess a certain number of markers to be included in downstream analysis. Maximum likelihood trees were generated using FastTree. Phylogenies were determined manually based on the location of each draft genome on the trees. 16S rRNA genes were also predicted and aligned to assign a putative phylogeny to draft genomes.

In total, 2,631 draft genomes were generated, with 1,491 of them being >70% complete and 420 meeting a high-quality threshold of >90% complete and <5% contamination.

uses_data:
The collected data in this study consists of chest radiographs (X-rays) and their associated radiology reports. The data was obtained from the MIMIC-CXR project, which is available on PhysioNet. Access to the data is controlled and requires user registration, completion of a credentialing process, and signing of a data use agreement.

The dataset includes images and reports organized into subfolders named according to the anonymous patient identifier. Each patient subfolder contains a single folder and a single text file for each imaging study made available for that patient.

The collected data underwent a de-identification process to remove any patient identifiers and protect patient privacy. The de-identification process involved several steps:

1. Clean descriptors option: Unstructured text data elements that provided no scientific value were removed. Useful data elements containing free-text were homogenized using manually curated look-up tables. Text not present in the look-up tables was removed. Longitudinal temporal information, such as modified dates, was retained to contextualize sequential chest radiographs for an individual patient.

2. Clean pixel data: After processing the DICOM meta-data, the image pixel values were de-identified. Images may contain "burned in" annotations, which are areas where pixel values have been modified to display text. These annotations may include patient identifiers. A custom algorithm was used to remove dates and patient identifiers while retaining radiologically relevant information, such as orientation. Optical character recognition was performed to detect text within the image, and any suspected text containing patient health information was obscured by setting the pixel values to black.

3. Clean graphics: Standard data elements that store overlay planes, graphics, or annotations were removed if present. The coordinates of the obscured text were stored in the Graphic Object Sequence data element.

The de-identification process was validated by manually reviewing all unique DICOM metadata attribute values, which did not contain any patient health information. Additionally, the pixel data of 6,900 radiographs were reviewed by two independent annotators, and no patient health information was found.

In addition to the MIMIC-CXR dataset, there are other related datasets that may complement future work. These include the JSRT Database, the Montgomery County chest X-ray set, the Shenzhen Hospital X-ray set, the Open-I Indiana University Chest X-ray dataset, the NIH ChestX-ray14 dataset, and the University of Alicante chest radiograph dataset. These datasets focus on various aspects of chest radiographs and may provide additional resources for research.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from the electronic health record (EHR) system at BIDMC. The collection process involved two stages. In the first stage, a cohort of patients was identified by querying the BIDMC EHR for chest radiograph studies acquired in the emergency department between 2011-2016. Only the patient identifiers associated with these studies were extracted. In the second stage, all chest radiographs and radiology reports available in the Radiology Information System (RIS) for this set of patients between 2011-2016 were extracted.

To ensure anonymity of the data, two sets of random identifiers were generated. First, a random identifier (subject_id) was generated for each patient in the range 10,000,000-19,999,999. Each patient was also assigned a date shift which mapped their first index admission year to a year between 2100-2200. This preserves the relative temporality of patient information while removing all information about seasonality or day of the week for the studies. Second, a random identifier (study_id) was generated for each study in the range 50,000,000-59,999,999. Multiple images may be associated with the same study, and they all have the same study_id.

The chest radiographs were sourced from the hospital picture archiving and communication system (PACS) in Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM) format. DICOM is a common format used in medical imaging devices. The DICOM format contains meta-data associated with the images, and the DICOM standard provides rules for the structure of this information. In this work, the DICOM Standard version 2017e was used.

To conform with HIPAA regulations, personal health information (PHI) was removed from both the DICOM meta-data and the pixel values. A de-identification strategy was followed, which involved removing or modifying specific data elements in the DICOM meta-data. The Basic Application Level Confidentiality Profile with the Clean Descriptors Option, Retain Longitudinal Temporal Information Modified Dates, Clean Pixel Data, and Clean Graphics options was used. The De-identification Method Code Sequence was set to a specific profile, and Patient Identity Removed was set to "YES" for all images.

The DICOMs were initially de-identified using Orthanc v1.0.0. New unique identifiers were generated for each image, and these identifiers were used as the filenames. Unique object identifiers (UIDs) were generated for the study, series, and instance (image) using the Universally Unique Identifier (UUID) approach. Anonymized identifiers for the patient and study were inserted into the DICOM data elements.

To access the data, users need to complete a course on human subjects research and sign a data use agreement. The data can be downloaded from the MIMIC-CXR Database project on PhysioNet. Jupyter Notebooks are provided to demonstrate usage of the data, and online documentation is available. The goal of releasing the dataset is to foster collaboration and accelerate research in medical image processing and secondary analysis of electronic health records.

collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:
- Electronic health record (EHR)
- Radiology Information System (RIS)
- Hospital picture archiving and communication system (PACS)
- Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM) format
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. Electronic health record (EHR): The BIDMC operates a locally built EHR, including a Radiology Information System (RIS), to store and process clinical and radiographic data.

2. Picture Archiving and Communication System (PACS): Chest radiographs were sourced from the hospital PACS in Digital Imaging and Communications in Medicine (DICOM) format. DICOM is a common format that facilitates interoperability between medical imaging devices.

3. Orthanc v1.0.0: Orthanc was used for de-identification of DICOMs. It generated new unique identifiers for each image and stored them as filenames.

4. Universally Unique Identifier (UUID): UIDs were generated using the UUID approach for the study, series, and instance (image) in the DICOM header.

5. Tesseract library v3.05.02: Optical character recognition (OCR) was performed using the Tesseract library to detect text within the images.

6. Custom algorithm: A custom algorithm was used to de-identify the image pixel values, removing dates and patient identifiers while retaining radiologically relevant information such as orientation.

7. Data elements and profiles: The DICOM standard provides data elements and profiles for de-identification, including the Basic Application Level Confidentiality Profile with the Clean Descriptors Option, Retain Longitudinal Temporal Information Modified Dates, Clean Pixel Data, and Clean Graphics options.

8. Manual review: All unique DICOM metadata attribute values were manually reviewed to ensure they did not contain PHI. The pixel data of 6,900 radiographs were also manually reviewed by two independent annotators.

Note: The code used to prepare the dataset cannot be made publicly available due to the use of real patient information during the de-identification process.
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involves several steps. First, unstructured text data elements that provided no scientific value were removed. Then, useful data elements containing free-text were homogenized using manually curated look-up tables. Text that was not present in the look-up tables was removed. 

Next, the longitudinal temporal information, such as modified dates, was retained. This information is important for contextualizing sequential chest radiographs for an individual patient. The dates stored in specific data elements were shifted using a patient-specific date shift methodology. The time of day was not modified during this process. 

After processing the DICOM meta-data, the image pixel values were de-identified. Images often contain "burned in" annotations, which are areas where pixel values have been modified to display text. These annotations may include patient identifiers, such as names and medical record numbers. The de-identification algorithm used an ensemble of image preprocessing and optical character recognition approaches to detect and remove text within the image. 

Additionally, graphics and annotations that contain PHI were removed from the data. The coordinates of the PHI obscuring black boxes used to clean the pixel data were stored in the Graphic Object Sequence data element. 

To validate the de-identification process, all unique DICOM metadata attribute values were manually reviewed and found to not contain PHI. The pixel data of 6,900 radiographs were also manually reviewed by two independent annotators, and no PHI was found. 

Overall, the annotation process involved removing unnecessary text, retaining important temporal information, de-identifying image pixel values, and removing graphics and annotations containing PHI.

uses_uses:
The recommended uses of the dataset are: 
1. Data processing pipeline: Read count normalization and sample quality control.
2. GenePattern pipeline: Processing of normalized and log transformed read counts per replicate sample.
3. Mapping shRNAs to gene symbols using a mapping file.
4. Calculation of joint entropy and mutual information between target profiles and essentiality profiles.
5. Estimation of significance of RNMI matching scores using an empirical permutation test.
6. Identification of context-specific dependencies and biomarkers associated with differential sensitivities.
7. Discovery of pathways to which specific tumor subtypes are preferentially dependent.
8. Exploration of molecular and cellular correlates of dependency profiles using the PARIS analytical tool.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: No. The data of the dataset does not represent people. The dataset is focused on genetic alterations in human cancers and the genetic vulnerabilities of cancer cells.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are cancer cell lines, not humans.
uses_data:
The collected data consists of several files and tables. The data files include a README file outlining the data processing steps, two.gct formatted files containing logged and normalized read counts from pooled screenings of different groups of cancer cell lines, and a table containing SNP genotypes per cell line. There is also a chip mapping file and three tables in either.xls or tab delimited text format. 

The data set was generated through short hairpin RNA (shRNA) screens in a large number of cell lines in a highly parallel manner. A pool of shRNA plasmids targeting ~11,000 genes was used to infect the cell lines, and the relative levels of the shRNA plasmids in the cell-pool gDNA were measured using Illumina-based sequencing. The data set facilitates the discovery of context-specific dependencies and biomarkers associated with these differential sensitivities. 

In addition to the shRNA level data, a gene-level dataset generated using the ATARiS algorithm is also available for download. The ATARiS algorithm combines data from multiple distinct shRNAs per target gene across many cell lines to reduce the contribution of off-target effects while reinforcing the on-target effects. The data set can be queried for specific genes, and the dependency profile for such genes across cell lines can be individually downloaded. 

The data set is hosted in the Project Achilles Portal, which also provides users with the ability to search the data for specific genes. The gene page contains information on the shRNAs targeting the gene, whether they contribute to the gene-summary score, and a consistency score representing the confidence that the observed phenotypic effects are the result of on-target gene suppression. A sortable heatmap with the shRNA and ATARiS scores per cell line is also shown. 

Overall, the data set provides a comprehensive resource for studying the genetic vulnerabilities of human cancer cells and identifying context-specific dependencies and biomarkers associated with these dependencies.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected from various sources, primarily the Cancer Cell Line Encyclopedia (CCLE). A total of 179 cell lines were obtained from CCLE, and information about the cell lines, including their source, is listed in the 'Table1_screening_information.xls' file. Tumor type and growth media conditions used for screening were also obtained from the CCLE project. For cell lines not obtained from CCLE, the media conditions used by the source laboratory were used.

The cell doubling time was calculated from lentivirally infected cells during the course of the experiment. Days in culture, calculated from the date of infection until the date of harvest, and passage number, based on the number of splits that occurred during the time in culture, refer to the time point of the sample that was used for data collection specific to each cell line.

The data files have been deposited in the FigShare data repository. The dataset includes a README file, four .gct formatted files, three tables in either .xls or tab delimited text format, and one .chip mapping file. The README file provides information about the data processing steps that occurred between the initial logged and normalized read count files and the final shRNA- and gene-level files. The .gct formatted files contain the logged and normalized read counts from the pooled screening of the cancer cell lines, with replicate cell lines in columns and shRNAs in rows. The .xls and tab delimited text files contain additional information related to the dataset.

To enhance dataset quality, cell line sample identity was tracked and confirmed after screening. SNP fingerprinting was performed to validate the cell line identity. Birdseed genotypes from Affymetrix SNP6.0 arrays for 79 SNPs were primarily used as references for cell line identity. The SNP genotyping results are listed in the 'Table 2_SNP_genotyping.xls' file, along with information about the fingerprinting platform used for comparison. Fluidigm or Sequenom fingerprints after screening were extracted and compared to the reference using the GenePattern module 'FPmatching'. This process confirms cell line identity in the screening results and ensures the correct use of previously collected genomic information from the CCLE project.

The dataset is available on the Project Achilles Portal, which was developed at the Broad Institute to make the Achilles datasets more visible and easily accessible to the scientific community. The datasets are organized by version, and data is available for download at the shRNA level and summarized at the gene level using the ATARiS algorithm. The gene-level scores are preferred for downstream analysis as they take into account the consistency of different shRNA values for one gene across cell lines, maximizing the on-target effects of shRNAs. In addition to the data files, the portal provides a sample information file, an shRNA to gene mapping file, and a detailed description of the processing steps for each version of the data. The data can be downloaded or launched using GENE-E. The portal also allows users to search for specific genes and provides information on shRNAs targeting those genes, including their contribution to the gene-summary score and a consistency score. A sortable heatmap with shRNA and ATARiS scores per cell line is also available.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data in the provided context.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Project Achilles Portal, shRNA screens, next generation sequencing, and the ATARiS algorithm.
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include the Project Achilles Portal, shRNA plasmids, Illumina-based sequencing, the ATARiS algorithm, GENE-E software, and the PARIS analytical tool.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process involves adding additional information to the data files. In this case, the shRNA table file contains annotation information for each shRNA, including consistency scores and whether each shRNA was used in the resulting gene solution. The cell line information file also contains annotations about screening conditions. Additionally, there is an shRNA to gene mapping file that maps each shRNA barcode sequence to a gene transcript identifier, gene identifier, and gene symbol. This annotation process helps provide more context and understanding to the data.

uses_data:
The collected data in the GIDMaPS dataset consists of standardized drought indices. These indices use a negative value to indicate a relatively dry spell and a positive value to indicate a wet spell. The dataset includes both the original standardized scale and the D-scale 12, which provides information on drought severity. The dataset also includes probability of drought occurrence computed for different drought severity levels. For example, the dataset provides the probability of a drought index below -0.8 or D1 drought severity. 

The GIDMaPS data sets are available to the public in a simple ASCII format, with each record containing the longitude, latitude, and drought severity. These data sets provide a static representation of the data at the time of publication, but there is also a periodically updating data distribution system that provides graphical images and raw data. 

The dataset includes prediction data sets that provide 1 to 6 month lead forecasts based on the indices mentioned above and the last monitoring data available. The system runs on a daily basis and updates the data record when new input data sets become available. 

The GIDMaPS data sets can be used for a wide variety of applications and studies. They can be used to assess the fraction of global land areas under different drought severity levels, investigate a region's drought climatology, evaluate drought duration and severity in historical records, assess changes in drought and heatwaves, study the effects of historical droughts on vegetation growth and ecosystem behavior, and analyze the impact of droughts on water, energy, and agricultural resources. The data sets can also provide valuable information for resource managers in decision making and disaster preparedness. 

It is important to note that the purpose of the GIDMaPS data sets is not to replace currently available dynamic models, but to provide additional drought information to improve current capabilities in drought monitoring and prediction.
collection_explanation:
The dataset used in this study is called GIDMaPS (Global Integrated Drought Monitoring and Prediction System). The data records in GIDMaPS are standardized drought indices, where a negative value indicates a relatively dry spell and a positive value indicates a wet spell. The monitoring component of GIDMaPS provides information on drought severity in both the original standardized scale and the D-scale. The D-scale is a classification system that categorizes drought severity levels. 

The prediction component of GIDMaPS offers probabilities of drought occurrence computed for different drought severity levels. For example, it provides the probability of a drought index below -0.8 or D1 drought severity. The prediction data sets provide 1 to 6 month lead forecasts based on the indices.

The GIDMaPS data sets are available to the public through an unrestricted repository in a simple ASCII format, which includes longitude, latitude, and drought severity. These data sets provide a static representation of the data at the time of publication. Additionally, there is a periodically updating data distribution system that provides graphical images and raw data.

The system runs on a daily basis and updates the data record whenever new input data sets become available. The data distribution system delivers both graphical images and raw data. Table 3 summarizes the GIDMaPS drought information outputs.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from GIDMaPS, Modern-Era Retrospective analysis for Research and Applications (MERRA-Land), North American Land Data Assimilation System (NLDAS), Global Land Data Assimilation System (GLDAS), Global Drought Climate Data Record (GDCDR), Precipitation Estimation from Remotely Sensed Information using Artificial Neural Networks (PERSIANN), and Global Precipitation Climatology Centre (GPCC).
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- Model simulations
- Remote sensing observations
- Modern-Era Retrospective analysis for Research and Applications (MERRA-Land)
- North American Land Data Assimilation System (NLDAS)
- Global Land Data Assimilation System (GLDAS)
- Global Drought Climate Data Record (GDCDR)
- Precipitation Estimation from Remotely Sensed Information using Artificial Neural Networks (PERSIANN) satellite data
- Global Precipitation Climatology Project (GPCP) observations
- Standardized Precipitation Index (SPI)
- Standardized Soil Moisture Index (SSI)
- Multivariate Standardized Drought Index (MSDI)
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves the monitoring component and the prediction component of the Global Integrated Drought Monitoring and Prediction System (GIDMaPS). The monitoring component provides information on drought severity in both the original standardized scale and the D-scale 12. The prediction component offers probability of drought occurrence computed for different drought severity levels. The data sets are available in a simple ASCII format and provide a static representation of the data at the time of publication. The system runs on a daily basis and updates the data record upon availability of new input data sets. The data sets can be used for a wide variety of applications/studies, such as assessing global land areas under different drought severity levels, investigating a region's drought climatology, evaluating drought duration and severity in historical records, studying the effects of droughts on vegetation growth and ecosystem behavior, and providing resource managers with valuable information for decision making and disaster preparedness. The purpose of GIDMaPS is not to replace currently available dynamic models, but to provide additional drought information to improve current capabilities in drought monitoring and prediction.

authoring_funding_grant_id: The mentioned grant reference numbers in the context are not provided.
authoring_maintenance_policies: No, there is no mention about maintenance policies of the dataset in the context.
uses_uses: The recommended uses of the dataset include analyzing phenotypic data for mental health and learning, evaluating the quality of imaging data, assessing correlations between different measures in the dataset, and developing and testing correction strategies for head motion in MRI data.
uses_ml_approach: No, there is no mention about any test using a machine learning approach.
uses_data_limits: No, there is no mention about non-recommended uses or generalization limits of the data.
uses_represents_people: Yes, the data of the dataset represents people. The dataset includes information on 10,000 children and adolescents residing in the New York City area, including behavioral and cognitive phenotyping, brain imaging, genetics, and other measures related to familial, environmental, and lifestyle variables.
uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are children and adolescents residing in the New York City area.
uses_biases: Yes, the context provides information about biases issues of the data. The context mentions that the resulting samples bring with them a wide range of biases, including symptom severity, sex distribution, and problems related to access to care. This indicates that there are biases present in the dataset.
uses_sensitivity: No. The context does not provide any information about the data being offensive or sensitive to some people.
uses_privacy: Yes, the context provides information about privacy issues of the data. The data is protected by a Data Usage Agreement (DUA) to ensure participant confidentiality and prevent breaches of privacy. Personal identifiers specified by HIPAA are removed, and a Certificate of Confidentiality is obtained to protect the privacy of human subjects. The DUA also ensures that data users agree to protect participant confidentiality and take necessary measures to prevent privacy breaches. No protected health identifiers are present in the distributed data to minimize the risk of privacy breach.
uses_data: The collected data includes phenotypic data, EEG data, eye-tracking data, and imaging data. The phenotypic data can be accessed through the COllaborative Informatics and Neuroimaging Suite (COINS) Data Exchange or an HBN-dedicated instance of the Longitudinal Online Research and Imaging System (LORIS). The phenotypic data, except for age, sex, and handedness, are protected by a Data Usage Agreement (DUA) that researchers must complete and have approved before accessing the data. The EEG, eye-tracking, and imaging data can be accessed through the 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project and its International Neuroimaging Data-sharing Initiative (FCP/INDI). The imaging data is stored in the Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) format. The data quality assessment for the imaging datasets collected through the HBN is consistent with previous data generation and sharing initiatives, and all imaging datasets are made available regardless of data quality. The phenotypic data are evaluated for outliers and the observed distributions and inter-relationships are assessed for sensibility. The imaging data quality is assessed using the Preprocessed Connectome Project Quality Assurance Protocol (QAP). The data license for the HBN datasets varies depending on the date of collection, with datasets collected before December 6, 2016 being distributed under the Creative Commons, Attribution Non-Commercial Share Alike 4.0 International Public License, and datasets collected after that date being distributed using the Creative Commons Attribution 4.0 International Public License. The HBN protocol includes four sessions, each approximately three hours in duration, and includes clinician-administered assessments such as the KSADS-COMP interview for deriving clinical diagnoses.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through multiple methods. Starting in December 2016, participants were asked to provide a saliva sample using the Oragene Discover DNA collection kit. This was done as an alternative to blood collection, which was initially planned but discontinued due to logistical challenges. In July 2017, blood samples were also collected in the participant's home by a local phlebotomy service. The resulting materials, both saliva and blood samples, were donated to the NIMH Genetics Repository for sharing.

In addition to the saliva and blood samples, starting in August 2017, age-appropriate participants were also asked to provide 1-2 deciduous 'baby' teeth. These teeth were collected into provided plastic tubes, labeled, and stored at room temperature until analysis.

Overall, the collection process involved obtaining genetic material through saliva and blood samples, as well as deciduous teeth, from the participants. These samples were then stored and donated for further analysis and sharing.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:

- Phenotypic data
- EEG, eye-tracking, and imaging data
- Genetics (saliva samples and blood samples)
- Deciduous 'baby' teeth collection
- MRI data (specifically addressing head motion)
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

1. COllaborative Informatics and Neuroimaging Suite (COINS) Data Exchange: Used for accessing phenotypic data.
2. Longitudinal Online Research and Imaging System (LORIS): Used for accessing phenotypic data.
3. 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project and its International Neuroimaging Data-sharing Initiative (FCP/INDI): Used for accessing EEG, eye-tracking, and imaging data.
4. Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) format: Used for storing imaging data.
5. Oragene Discover (OGR-500) DNA collection kit: Used for collecting saliva samples for genetics.
6. Local phlebotomy service: Contracted for collecting blood samples for genetics.
7. Plastic tubes: Used for collecting deciduous 'baby' teeth.
8. Data analysis techniques: Used for handling head motion in MRI data, such as regressing a model of movement, removing motion-related spatial patterns, attenuating motion spikes, removing offending frames, and statistical corrections at the group level.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves evaluating the quality of the data and assessing the distribution and inter-relationships of the phenotypic and imaging data. For phenotypic data, outliers are checked and the observed distributions and inter-relationships are evaluated to ensure they make sense. Correlations between different measures are also analyzed. For imaging data, a Quality Assurance Protocol (QAP) is used to assess data quality, including measures such as functional MRI, morphometry MRI, and diffusion MRI. The impact of head motion during MRI scans is also examined. The annotated data can be accessed through the COllaborative Informatics and Neuroimaging Suite (COINS) Data Exchange or the Longitudinal Online Research and Imaging System (LORIS) with a Data Usage Agreement (DUA) in place to protect participant confidentiality. EEG, eye-tracking, and imaging data can be accessed through the 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project and its International Neuroimaging Data-sharing Initiative (FCP/INDI). There are also special opportunities to derive optimal measure sets that minimize the number of items required to characterize an individual while maximizing their predictive value, as well as the use of voice analysis for biomarker identification.
annotation_manual: The annotations have been done manually.
annotation_team_type: The context does not provide information about whether the data was annotated by an internal team, an external team, or a crowdsourcing team.
annotation_infrastructure:
Yes, the following tools or infrastructures have been used during the annotation process:

- Quality Assurance Protocol (QAP)
- COllaborative Informatics and Neuroimaging Suite (COINS) Data Exchange
- Longitudinal Online Research and Imaging System (LORIS)
- 1,000 Functional Connectomes Project
- International Neuroimaging Data-sharing Initiative (FCP/INDI)
- Preprocessed Connectome Project Quality Assurance Protocol (QAP)
- Brain Imaging Data Structure (BIDS) format
annotation_validation_methods: The context does not provide information about the validation methods used to validate the labels.
column122: No. The context does not provide any information about the demographic characteristics of the team who annotate the data.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of genomic, genetic, and covariate data for a defined set of samples. The data is available for studies A-D and can be found in the Sage Bionetworks AMP-AD Knowledge Portal. Each sample within a study has a unique sample ID that is consistent across all files within the study and files in other studies where applicable. The relationship between the studies and sample overlaps is illustrated in Figure 1. 

The data files are deposited in the AMP-AD Knowledge Portal and are accessible through the Synapse repository. A subset of the files for the Mayo LOAD GWAS and the Mayo eGWAS are also available via NIAGADS. The data files are annotated using a standard vocabulary to enable users to search for relevant content across the AMP-AD datasets using programmatic queries. 

The data described in the paper is controlled by the institutional review board (IRB) at the Mayo Clinic. Access to the data requires registration for a Synapse account and agreement to the data use terms. The data use terms include maintaining data in a secure and confidential manner, respecting the privacy of study participants, citing the data contributors in any publications resulting from data use, and informing data contributors of resultant publications. 

The molecular data includes information on sample collection and processing. For the Mayo LOAD GWAS, DNA samples were collected and processed as previously described. For the antemortem Mayo Clinic Jacksonville and Mayo Clinic Rochester series, whole blood samples were collected and DNA was extracted. For the postmortem Mayo Clinic Brain Bank series, cerebellar tissue was used for DNA extraction. Whole genome amplification (WGA) was applied to samples with limited amounts of DNA. 

The technical validation of the data includes quality control (QC) methods. For the Mayo LOAD GWAS, subjects with low genotyping call rates, duplicate genotyping, and sex-mismatches were eliminated from the dataset. SNPs with low genotyping call rates, minor allele frequencies, and Hardy-Weinberg p values were also eliminated. The Mayo eGWAS data included probes that have genetic variants within their sequence, and detection rates above background were calculated for each probe. Replicate samples were included for QC purposes. 

For the Mayo Pilot RNAseq data, outliers were identified using principal components analysis (PCA) and covariate data for these subjects were set to missing. Sex discrepancies were also assessed based on Y chromosome gene expression. Outliers and subjects with mis-matched sex were set to missing in the covariate files. 

At the time of publication, the Mayo RNAseq subjects did not have GWAS genotypes deposited on Synapse.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected through the collection and processing of DNA samples. For the Mayo LOAD GWAS, DNA samples were collected from whole blood samples using 10 ml EDTA tubes. DNA extraction was performed using the AutoGenFlex STAR instrument. For the postmortem Mayo Clinic Brain Bank series, DNA extraction was performed using cerebellar tissue and the Wizard Genomic DNA purification kit. Due to limited amounts of DNA in the Mayo Clinic Rochester series and Mayo Clinic Brain Bank series, whole genome amplification (WGA) was applied using the Illustra GenomiPhi V2 DNA Amplification Kit. The WGA reactions utilized 5-15 ng genomic DNA as a template.
collection_team_type: The data was collected by an internal team.
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources: The data has been collected from DNA samples, whole blood samples, cerebellar tissue, and RNAseq datasets.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:

- AutoGenFlex STAR instrument (AutoGen) for DNA extraction from whole blood samples
- Wizard Genomic DNA purification kit (Promega) for DNA extraction from cerebellar tissue
- Illustra GenomiPhi V2 DNA Amplification Kit (GE Healthcare Bio-Sciences) for whole genome amplification (WGA)
- Synapse software platform for data storage and access
- Amazon Web Services (AWS) for cloud-based storage
- Sage Bionetworks AMP-AD Knowledge Portal for data hosting
- HT-Seq and SNAPR for generating read counts in RNAseq datasets
- edgeR implementation of the trimmed mean of M-values (TMM) normalization method for count normalization
annotation_explanation:
The annotation process done over the data involved several steps. 

For the Mayo LOAD GWAS data, quality control (QC) methods were applied to eliminate subjects with low genotyping call rates, duplicate genotyping, sex-mismatches, and SNPs with low genotyping call rates, minor allele frequencies, and Hardy-Weinberg p values. After QC, the dataset included 313,504 SNP genotypes from 2,099 subjects.

For the Mayo eGWAS data, probes were annotated for the presence of genetic variants by comparing their positions to those of variants within dbSNP131. Probes that had at least one variant within their sequence were identified. The annotation included information on whether the probe sequence harbored a SNP and the detection rate above background for each probe within each analytic group. Replicate samples were also included for quality control purposes.

For the Mayo Pilot RNAseq data, principal components analysis (PCA) was used to identify outliers in the AD and PSP cohorts. Covariates for these subjects were set to missing. The RNASeq data was also assessed for sex discrepancies based on Y chromosome gene expression, and subjects with mismatched sex were identified and their covariate data set to missing.

Overall, the annotation process involved QC measures, identification of genetic variants within probe sequences, detection rate calculations, identification of outliers, and identification of subjects with sex discrepancies.

uses_collected_from_people: No. The subjects of the collection process are not humans. The data collected consists of aggregated topographic variables derived from two main data sources, the GMTED and the SRTM datasets.
uses_data: The collected data in this study consists of aggregated topographic variables derived from two main data sources: the 250 m GMTED and the 90 m SRTM4.1dev. The GMTED dataset was chosen for its global coverage and high resolution, while the SRTM dataset was used for comparison and validation purposes. The GMTED dataset is a composite product based on several gridded elevation data sources, with the main source being NGA's SRTM Digital Terrain Elevation Data. Additional data sources were used to fill gaps in coverage and to improve accuracy. The GMTED dataset was standardized to a spatial grain of 250 m and includes five layers with values for mean, median, minimum, maximum, and standard deviation. The root-mean-square error (RMSE) for the GMTED dataset ranges from 25 to 42 m for the 1 km product, 29 to 32 m for the 500 m product, and 26 to 30 m for the 250 m product. The SRTM dataset has a spatial resolution of 90 m and covers low latitude areas between 60N and 58S. It consists of a single value of altitude per grid cell. Both datasets are available for download in a compressed GeoTiff file format in the WGS84 coordinate reference system. The data can be recomputed at the original resolution on demand.
collection_explanation: The dataset was collected by assembling readily available data of high quality. The authors designed the study and developed and implemented the computational methodology and processing chain to derive all derived continuous/categorical variables. They standardized and validated the dataset layers. The authors also prepared the web-mapping platform and the downloading procedure. The dataset includes a rich stack of global environmental information, particularly in regards to terrain. To address the lack of readily available topographic variables at a global extent, the authors calculated a suite of elevation-derived topographic variables based on the 250 m Global Multi-resolution Terrain Elevation Data 2010 dataset (GMTED). They also calculated the most relevant variables using the widely used 90 m Shuttle Radar Topographic Mission (SRTM) dataset. The derived topographic variables include mi, ma, and sd elevation variables obtained from the GMTED source layers, as well as 16 additional derived topographic variables, including 15 continuous and 1 categorical variable. The categorical variable represents the most common landforms and has 10 geomorphological classes. The derived variables are based on the GMTED median elevation. The dataset also includes aggregated topographic variables based on spatial aggregation approaches to characterize global topographic heterogeneity.
collection_team_type: Internal team
collection_team_demographic: No, there is no mention of demographic information about the team who collects the data.
collection_sources:
The data has been collected from the following sources or subjects:
- Intergovernmental Platform for Biodiversity and Ecosystem Services (IPBES)
- Map of Life (https://www.mol.org)
- GMTED (Global Multi-resolution Terrain Elevation Data 2010 dataset)
- SRTM (Shuttle Radar Topographic Mission 22,23 void filled dataset SRTM4.1dev 24,25)
- Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL, http://www.gdal.org/)
- Geographic Resources Analysis Support System software (GRASS, https://grass.osgeo.org/)
- Processing Kernel for geospatial data (pktools, http://pktools.nongnu.org)
collection_infrastructure: The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include open-source software, the Yale Center for Research Computing at Yale University, the Geospatial Data Abstraction Library (GDAL), the Geographic Resources Analysis Support System software (GRASS), the Processing Kernel for geospatial data (pktools), and a customized python script. These tools were used for parallel and distributed processing, computation of derived variables, aggregation of variables, and validation of dataset layers.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves calculating a suite of elevation-derived topographic variables based on the 250 m Global Multi-resolution Terrain Elevation Data (GMTED) dataset and the 90 m Shuttle Radar Topographic Mission (SRTM) dataset. These variables are then resampled or aggregated to coarser spatial grains (1, 5, 10, 50, 100 km) using different spatial aggregation approaches. The resulting variables are ready to use as input data in various environmental models and analyses. Additionally, the code is provided to calculate user-specified variables on custom spatial grains. The annotated data is available for download and visualization.
annotation_team_type: The data was annotated by an internal team.
annotation_infrastructure: Yes, the tools and infrastructures used during the annotation process are GDAL, GRASS, and pktools.

uses_data:
The collected data consists of three datasets: the classification data, the raw classification data, and the consensus classification data. 

The classification data includes information about each image, such as the URL for retrieving the image and the unique identifier for each capture event and resultant image set. 

The raw classification data includes information about each classification event, including the unique identifier for each capture event, the unique identifier for each classification event, the user ID or session ID, the species selected from a list of options, the count of individuals, and binary indicators for standing, resting, moving, eating, interacting, and babies. 

The consensus classification data includes the results of applying the plurality algorithm to the raw classification data. It includes the unique identifier for each capture event, the number of images in the image set, the date and time stamp, the site ID, the UTM coordinates of the site, the number of species in the capture event, the species of animal, the median number of individuals, and the proportions of users who selected each behavior for each species. 

These datasets can be used for various purposes, including ecological research, citizen-science research, machine learning, and computer vision. They can be used to evaluate population and community dynamics, develop more complex aggregation algorithms, and train machine-learning algorithms. The datasets are publicly available at Dryad.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected through the Snapshot Serengeti camera survey, which deployed 225 camera traps across a 1,125 km2 area in the Serengeti National Park, Tanzania from 2010-2013. The camera traps captured full-resolution images, which were then processed using a citizen science website called Snapshot Serengeti. 

The citizen science interface allowed volunteers to classify the images by identifying the species present, the number of individuals, and the behavioral activity or presence of young. Each image set was classified by multiple volunteers, and the classifications were aggregated using a simple plurality algorithm. The species with the most "votes" from the volunteers was assigned as the aggregated answer, and the number of individuals for each identified species was calculated as the median number reported by all volunteers. 

To assess the accuracy of the aggregated classifications, an evenness index was calculated. When all classifications were in agreement, indicating high accuracy, a value of zero was assigned. Otherwise, Pielou's evenness index was used, which ranges from 0 to 1. A value of 0 indicates low evenness and high accuracy, while a value of 1 indicates high evenness and low accuracy. However, the Pielou evenness index is expected to be high for image sets with multiple species, so it is not a useful gauge of accuracy in those cases. 

In addition to the aggregated classifications, the dataset also includes raw classification data, which consists of all individual classifications made by all users on all image sets. This raw classification data can be used to develop and test algorithms that employ user weighting or apply a Bayesian framework to incorporate information about species likelihood based on previous or subsequent images. 

The dataset also includes consensus data, which consists of a single classification per image set produced by applying the consensus algorithm to the raw classifications. The consensus data also includes image metadata such as the date, time, and location of each image. 

Furthermore, the dataset includes operation dates, which provide metadata of when each camera was operational. This information was extracted from the image EXIF data and includes the start and end dates of valid photographs on a given SD card. 

Lastly, the dataset includes gold-standard data, which consists of expert classifications for a subset of 4,149 image sets. Multiple experts reviewed all images for which any single expert expressed uncertainty, resulting in more accurate classifications compared to those provided by a single expert. In a small percentage of images, the panel of experts agreed that no authoritative species identification could be made, and these images are marked as "impossible." The gold-standard data includes the number of species in each image set, the identified species, and the estimated number of individuals.

collection_infrastructure:
The tools, devices, and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- Crowdsourcing and citizen science methods
- Plurality algorithm for consensus dataset
- Raw classification dataset
- Data Records available at Dryad
- URL information for retrieving images
- University of Minnesota Supercomputing Institute for image access
- CaptureEventID for unique identification
- UserID for user identification
- Species list for classification
- Count for estimating the number of individuals
- Binary indicators for standing, resting, moving, eating, interacting, and babies
- Metadata for ecological analyses
- UTM X and Y coordinates for location
- SiteID for site code
- DateTime stamp in UTC + 3:00 time zone
- Higher education curriculum development for teaching scientific method
- Graduate level coursework in ecology, informatics, and computer vision
- Applications in basic and applied ecology, citizen-science research, machine learning, and computer vision
- Use of raw citizen-science answers for developing aggregation algorithms
- Use of human-annotated sets of imagery for training machine-learning algorithms.
annotation_explanation: The annotation process done over the data involves crowdsourcing and citizen science. Users classify images by selecting a species from a list of options or marking it as 'blank' if there is no animal present. They also provide additional information such as the number of individuals, their behavior (standing, resting, moving, eating, interacting), and the presence of young. The raw classification dataset includes one record per unique user, capture event, and species. The consensus dataset is derived from a plurality algorithm applied to the raw classification data, resulting in a single classification per capture event. Measures of uncertainty and difficulty are provided for each species classified in a capture event. The consensus dataset also includes metadata such as date-time stamp, location, and the number of images in the capture event. This annotated dataset is used for various applications in ecology, informatics, computer vision, and education.
annotation_manual: The annotations have been done manually.
annotation_team_type: The data was annotated by a combination of an external team (crowdsourcing) and citizen science.
annotation_infrastructure:
Yes, the tools and infrastructures used during the annotation process are:
- The Snapshot Serengeti web interface developed using the Zooniverse's platform Ouroboros, written in Ruby on Rails.
- A custom-built JavaScript front-end for volunteer classifiers to classify image sets.
- A MongoDB datastore to save the classification results.
- The consensus dataset derived from a plurality algorithm.
- The code used to create the Snapshot Serengeti web interface is publicly available at https://github.com/zooniverse/serengeti.
- The scripts used to process the data and calculate the consensus classifications are publicly available at https://github.com/mkosmala/SnapshotSerengetiScripts.
annotation_validation_methods: The context does not provide information about the validation methods used to validate the labels.

uses_data:
The collected data for the Brain Genomics Superstruct Project (GSP) is available for download from the Harvard Dataverse Network and the LONI Image Data Archive. The dataset includes structural, functional, and behavioral measures for 1,570 participants. The imaging data is stored in 10 separate tar files, each containing 157 subjects. All 10 tar files must be downloaded to obtain the full dataset. There is also a single description comma separated value (.csv) file that contains demographic and phenotype data for all 1,570 subjects. 

In addition, there is a separate tar file for test-retest data, which includes both sessions for each of the 69 test-retest participants. A description .csv file is included for the test-retest subjects as well. 

The extended release dataset includes an additional .csv file with an extended set of phenotypes. Access to the extended release dataset requires users to sign and submit a separate GSP Restricted Data Use Terms application to the Harvard Neuroinformatics Research Group. Access to the extended release dataset is restricted to Principal Investigators (PIs) of scientific research or users who provide the name of an approved PI overseeing their research. 

All phenotypic data are stored in .csv files, and a description of the phenotypes included in the dataset is provided in the GSP_README_140630.pdf file. Some phenotypes are separately available for download as part of the extended data release. 

The data collection and anonymization procedures employed in the GSP have resulted in a dataset that is highly suitable for processing, with minimal restrictions and without dependencies on proprietary tools. The neuroimaging data is converted to NIfTI-1 file format, anonymized, and assessed for data quality using publicly accessible processing tools. 

Data security measures were implemented to protect the data, including user authentication and role-based access controls in the eXtensible Neuroimaging Archive Toolkit (XNAT) system. Only users with read privilege to a specific project can view the data assigned to that project.
collection_explanation:
The dataset was collected as part of the Brain Genomics Superstruct Project (GSP). The collection process involved the collection of saliva samples using two Oragene saliva kits. The initial saliva sample was collected from each participant immediately prior to the scan, and a second saliva sample was collected immediately following the scan for backup purposes. It is important to note that the genetic data collected from the saliva samples are not included in this initial data release, but are planned for release in the future.

To obtain the dataset, users can download the 'Brain Genomics Superstruct Project (GSP)' initial release dataset of structural, functional, and behavioral measures from the Harvard Neuroinformatics Research Group website. Step-by-step instructions for accessing the dataset are available on the 'Request Access' page of the website. The dataset is available in the Harvard Dataverse Network and can also be downloaded from the LONI Image Data Archive.

The dataset is stored in 10 separate tar files, each containing 157 subjects. To obtain the full dataset, all 10 tar files must be downloaded. In addition, there is a single description comma separated value (.csv) file (GSP_list_140630.csv) in the study 'Documentation' section that contains the demographic and phenotype data for all 1,570 unique subjects. For test-retest data, there is a single tar file (GSP_retest_140630.tar) that contains both sessions for each of the 69 test-retest participants. A description .csv file (GSP_retest_140630.csv) for the test-retest subjects is also included.

There is an extended set of phenotypes available for download, which can be obtained from the LONI Image Data Archive. However, access to the extended phenotypes requires users to sign and submit a separate GSP Restricted Data Use Terms application to the Harvard Neuroinformatics Research Group. Access to the extended release dataset is restricted to Principal Investigators (PIs) of scientific research or users who provide the name of an approved PI overseeing their research.

The GSP dataset was collected using a rapid acquisition protocol that was added to existing neuroimaging research studies of healthy control participants. The total acquisition time for the basic protocol was approximately 15 minutes, while more extensive imaging took around 30 minutes. The imaging sequences were brief, with the T1 weighted structural image taking about 2 minutes and each resting-state functional MRI scan taking about 6 minutes. This allowed for a large sample size to be acquired quickly and reduced the risk of movement during the scans. However, it also led to attrition as there were no backup sequences if data quality was compromised.

The GSP dataset was collected from a convenience sample of individuals from the Boston community, which often included well-educated individuals with relatively high IQs. The estimated IQ scores in the dataset are positively shifted relative to the general population. However, certain personality traits, such as negative affect, have distributions that would be expected in a clinically-screened population-based sample. Therefore, when analyzing the GSP data, it is important to consider its demographic properties.

collection_sources: The data has been collected from the Brain Genomics Superstruct Project (GSP) and the LONI Image Data Archive.
collection_infrastructure:
The tools and infrastructure used during the collection process include:
- Large-scale imaging datasets
- Neuroimaging, behavioral, cognitive, and personality data
- Publicly accessible processing tools for data conversion, anonymization, and data quality estimation
- The Harvard Dataverse Network for data storage and download
- The LONI Image Data Archive as an additional option for data download
- The eXtensible Neuroimaging Archive Toolkit (XNAT) for data security and storage
annotation_explanation: The annotation process for the data involves storing all phenotypic information in .csv files. A description of the phenotypes included in the release can be found in the Supplementary Appendix D and the GSP_README_140630.pdf file. Some phenotypes are separately available for download as part of an extended data release. The dataset can be obtained by following step-by-step instructions provided on the 'Request Access' page of the GSP website. The data is available for download through the Harvard Dataverse Network and the LONI Image Data Archive. The dataset consists of imaging data stored in 10 separate tar files, each containing 157 subjects, and a single description .csv file (GSP_list_140630.csv) containing demographic and phenotype data for all 1,570 unique subjects. Test-retest data is stored separately in a single tar file (GSP_retest_140630.tar) and includes a description .csv file (GSP_retest_140630.csv) for the 69 test-retest subjects. An extended set of phenotypes is available for download from the LONI Image Data Archive, but access requires a separate application process. The annotation process is designed to provide restricted access to qualified users for legitimate scientific research purposes. The imaging data is available in NIfTI-1 file format, and Table 1 provides descriptions of the available sequences. The structural images are T1-weighted multi-echo MPRAGE images collected with 1.2 mm isotropic resolution. The BOLD data acquisitions include four timepoints before T1-stabilization, which should be discarded for most BOLD series analyses.
